  = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| demographics2_info2     = \n| demographics2_name3     = \n| demographics2_info3     = \n| blank_name_sec1         = [[Official language]]s\n| blank_info_sec1         = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| blank1_name_sec1        = \n| blank1_info_sec1        = 30 December 1981,<br>2002 (statute revised),<br>2007 (revised again)<ref>{{cite book |last=Magone|first= Jos\u00e9|title=Contemporary Spanish Politics|year=2008|publisher=Taylor & Francis|chapter=|pages=|isbn=978-0-415-42189-8}}</ref>\n| blank_name_sec2         = \n| blank_info_sec2         = \n| blank1_name_sec2        = \n| blank1_info_sec2        = \n| blank2_name_sec2        = \n| blank2_info_sec2        = \n| postal_code_type        = [[ISO 3166-2:ES|ISO 3166-2]]\n| postal_code             = 31160\n| governing_body          = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| leader_party            = \n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Orcoyen''' ({{lang-eu|Orkoien}}) is a town and [[municipality]] located in the province and autonomous community of [[Navarre]], northern [[Spain]], being part of Pamplona's metropolitan area. Its population currently stands at 3,637 inhabitants. Its population density is of 0.69 inhabitants/km<sup>2</sup>.\nThis area is home to one of Spain's most industrious regions, which is Pamplona's metropolitan area; this has triggered a transition from an agricultural background, giving way to the automotive industry.\n\n==Languages==\n[[Image:Navarra - Mapa densidad euskera 2001.svg|thumb|210px|right|Map showing density of [[Basque language|Basque]] speakers]]\n[[Spanish language|Spanish]] is the official language throughout Navarre. [[Basque language|Basque]] also has official status in the Basque-speaking area.<ref name=\"parlamentodenavarra.es\">{{cite web |url=http://www.parlamentodenavarra.es/home.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-11-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/