n| Long gun\n| \n|A former employee opened fire with a shotgun at a Western Forest Products mill, killing two employees and wounding two others.\n|-\n|[[Moncton shooting]]\n|June 4, 2014\n|[[Moncton]], [[New Brunswick]]\n|3\n| Long gun\n| No\n|24-year-old from Moncton, shot five armed officers from the Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP), killing three and severely injuring two.<ref>{{cite web|title=Moncton shootings: 3 RCMP officers dead, 2 wounded|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/moncton-shootings-3-rcmp-officers-dead-2-wounded-1.2665359|website=CBC|accessdate=October 24, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[2014 Edmonton killings]] \n|December 29, 2014\n|[[Edmonton, Alberta]]\n|8\n|\n| Yes\n| 53-year-old Phu Lam shot and killed 7 in one Edmonton residence, then went to a home in south Edmonton where he killed Cyndi Duong because he found he was raising a child that was not biologically his own. Phu Lam was found the next day after committing suicide in Fort Saskatchewan.\n|-\n|[[La Loche shootings]]\n|January 22, 2016\n|[[La Loche]], [[Saskatchewan]]\n| 4 / 7\n| Long gun\n| No\n|A 17-year-old student, whose identity is protected by youth justice publication ban, convicted of killing two of his cousins at their home, then going to [[La Loche Community School]] and continued firing, killing a teacher and an assistant, and wounding seven others. School Shooting.<ref>https://globalnews.ca/news/6110038/adult-sentence-upheld-in-la-loche-school-shooter-appeal/</ref>\n|-\n|[[Scarborough crossbow attack]]\n|August 25, 2016\n|[[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]], [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n|3\n| Crossbow\n| No\n|35-year-old Brett Ryan<ref>{{cite web|title=Man charged in Toronto crossbow killings is a convicted bank robber|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/crossbow-scarborough-deaths-1.3736694|website=cbc.ca|publisher=CBC|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref> killed 3 people and wounded 2 others with a crossbow before being apprehended by police.\n|-\n|[[Quebec City mosque shooting]]\n|January 29, 2017\n|[[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]]\n| 6\n| Handgun\n| No\n| [[Quebec City mosque shooting#Perpetrator|Alexandre Bissonnette]] (a former [[University of Laval]] student) killed 6 people and wounded 18 others at the [[Islamic Cultural Centre of Quebec City]].<ref>{{cite news|title=6 dead, 2 arrested after shooting at Quebec City mosque|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/quebec-city-mosque-gun-shots-1.3957686|accessdate=January 30, 2017|agency=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=January 20, 2017|language=English}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Toronto van attack]]\n|April 23, 2018\n|[[North York]], [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n|10\n| Vehicle\n| No\n| Single driver, Alek Minassian killed 10 people and wounded 15 others in a [[vehicle-ramming attack]] at Yonge Street, North York City Centre.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/pedestrians-struck-white-van-1.4631564|title=9 dead, 16 injured after van strikes pedestrians in North York|work=[[CBC News]]|date=April 23, 2018|access-date=April 23, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Danforth shooting]]\n|July 22, 2018\n|[[Greektown, Toronto]]\n|3 (including the gunman)\n| Hand gun\n| Yes\n|The 29-year-old gunman, Faisal Hussain, shot 10 people before fatally shooting himself. An 18-year-old woman was pronounced dead after she was taken to the hospital from gunshot wounds, and a critically injured 10-year-old girl was also pronounced dead after being taken to hospital.<ref name=\"globe\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/toronto/article-one-dead-13-injured-gunman-killed-in-toronto-mass-shooting/|title=Three dead, including shooter, 12 injured in Toronto mass shooting}}</ref>\"\n|-\n|[[Fredericton shooting]]\n|August 10, 2018\n|[[Fredericton, New Brunswick]]\n| 4\n| Long gun\n| No\n|48-year-old accused, Matthew Vincent Raymond, shot 4 people, 2 civilians Bobbie-Lee Wright and Donnie Robichaud, along with officers Robb Costello and Sara Burns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/matthew-raymond-fredericton-police-murder-trial-1.5064326|title=Accused Fredericton shooter Matthew Raymond will stand trial Sept. 30}}</ref>\n|-\n|Salmon Arm Church of Christ shooting\n|April 14, 2019\n|[[Salmon Arm]], [[British Columbia]]\n|1 / 1 / 0\n| Shooting\n|No\n|Matrix Savage Gathergood, 25, was charged with first-degree murder of Gordon Parmenter, aggravated assault and disguise with intent to commit an indictable offence in connection with the shooting on April 15.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/salmon-arm-shooting-charges-1.5098750|title=25-year-old charged with murder after deadly shooting at Salmon Arm church|last=|first=|date=April 15, 2019|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522170801/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/salmon-arm-shooting-charges-1.5098750|archive-date=May 22, 2019|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|Penticton shootings\n|April 15, 2019\n|[[Penticton]], [[British Columbia]]\n|4\n| Long gun\n| No\n|Four people killed in three different locations by a man reported to have used a rifle, and who immediately turned himself in to police.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/penticton-shootings-live-updates-and-what-we-know-so-far |title = Penticton shootings: Live updates and what we know so far &#124; Vancouver Sun|date = April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[2019 Northern British Columbia murders]]\n|July 14-19, 2019\n|[[British Columbia]]\n|3\n| Long gun\n| Yes\n|An Australian and an American tourist were found dead. Five days later, another man was found dead.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.insider.com/british-columbia-murders-missing-teens-link-rcmp-2019-7 |title = 2 murders, a death, and 2 disappearances in a remote, wild part of Canada could all be connected, police say}}</ref> On July 23, the RCMP initiated a country-wide manhunt for the two outstanding suspects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/ten-days-four-provinces-how-two-b-c-suspected-fugitives-continue-to-evade-rcmp|title=Ten days, four provinces: How two B.C. fugitives continue to evade RCMP {{!}} National Post|last=News|last2=Canada|date=2019-07-29|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> On August 7, two bodies, later identified as the suspects, were found in dense brush near the [[Nelson River]] in [[Manitoba]]. Autopsies and press conference reported death by suicide.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/rcmp-significant-announcement-1.5239053|title=Bodies found in northern Manitoba believed to be 2 B.C. fugitives: RCMP|last=Glowacki |first=Laura|date=August 7, 2019|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=August 7, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[2019 Markham home massacre]]\n|July 28, 2019\n|[[Markham, Ontario]]\n| 4\n| Knife\n| No\n|23-year-old Menhaz Zaman is charged after allegedly killing four family members by cutting their throats in a Markham home.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://toronto.citynews.ca/2019/07/28/four-bodies-found-in-markham-ont-home-one-man-in-custody/ | title=Four bodies found in Markham, Ont., home; one man in custody}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Nova Scotia killings]]\n|April 18-19, 2020\n|Multiple locations in [[Nova Scotia]]\n| At least 17 (including the gunman)\n| Unknown firearms\n| Unknown\n|51-year-old Gabriel Wortman, shot and killed at least 16 people, including a Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP) officer Heidi Stevenson, and later died himself.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html</ref> <ref>https://nationalpost.com/pmn/news-pmn/canada-news-pmn/newsalert-const-heidi-stevenson-identified-as-rcmp-officer-killed-in-shooting/amp</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of conflicts in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}{{massacres}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:M}}\n[[Category:Lists of massacres by country|Canada]]\n[[Category:Canada history-related lists|massacres]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Canada| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of disasters in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "MGHuc", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eList", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_massacres_in_Canada"}
{"title_page": "Tom Jones (singer)", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Welsh singer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Tom Jones\n| honorific_prefix = Sir\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=UK|size=100|OBE}}\n| image            = Sir Tom Jones at The Queen's Birthday Party (cropped-2).jpg\n| caption          = Jones at [[The Queen's Birthday Party]] in 2018\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Thomas John Woodward<ref name=\"closeup\"/>\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1940|6|7}}\n| birth_place      = [[Treforest]], [[Pontypridd]], [[Glamorgan]], Wales\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*Pop\n*[[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]\n*[[soul music|soul]]\n*[[country music|country]]\n*[[gospel music|gospel]]\n}}\n| occupation       = Singer\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 1963\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n*[[Decca Records|Decca]]\n*[[Epic Records|Epic]]\n*[[Jive Records|Jive]]\n*[[Island Records|Island]]\n*[[Mercury Records|Mercury]]\n*[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]\n*[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n*[[V2 Records|V2]]\n*[[S-Curve Records|S-Curve]]\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|www.tomjones.com}}\n}}\n'''Sir Thomas John Woodward''' {{post-nominals|country=UK|size=100%|OBE}} (born 7 June 1940),<ref>[https://www.tomjones.com/bio  Biography, ''TomJones.com''] Retrieved 2 April 2020</ref> known professionally as '''Tom Jones''', is a [[Wales|Welsh]] singer. His career began with a string of top-ten hits in the mid-1960s. He has toured regularly, with appearances in Las Vegas (1967\u20132011). Jones\u2019 voice has been described by [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] as a \"full-throated, robust baritone\".<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/tom-jones-mn0000609396|title=Tom Jones|publisher=[[AllMusic]] |first= Stephen Thomas| last= Erlewine| accessdate= 3 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis performing range has included pop, [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]], [[show tune]]s, [[country music|country]], dance, [[soul music|soul]] and [[gospel music|gospel]].  In 2008, the ''New York Times'' called Jones a musical \"shape shifter\",<ref name=\"nyt01\"/> who could  \"slide from soulful rasp to pop croon, with a voice as husky as it was pretty\".<ref name= \"nyt01\">{{cite news | title = A Hip Shaker in His Prime, Among Hip Friends  | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | first = Greg | last= Evans | date = 13 April 2008  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/13/arts/television/13evan.html | accessdate=}}</ref> Jones has sold over 100&nbsp;million records, with 36 [[Top 40]] hits in the UK and 19 in the US, including  \"[[It's Not Unusual]]\", \"[[What's New Pussycat? (song)|What's New Pussycat]]\", the [[Thunderball (soundtrack)#Title theme change|theme song]] for the 1965 [[James Bond]] film ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'', \"[[Green, Green Grass of Home]]\", \"[[Delilah (Tom Jones song)|Delilah]]\", \"[[She's a Lady]]\", \"[[Kiss (Art of Noise song)|Kiss]]\" and \"[[Sex Bomb]]\".<ref>{{cite magazine| url= https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_wBeEDJhw110C |page= [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_wBeEDJhw110C/page/n27/mode/2up/search/tom+jones 28] |title= Celebrating Songs for 40 Years| work= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=20 June 2009 |accessdate=12 October 2015 |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |via= archive.org}}</ref>\n\nJones made his acting debut playing the lead role in the 1979 television film ''[[Pleasure Cove]]''. He played himself in [[Tim Burton]]'s 1996 film ''[[Mars Attacks!]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/7-things-you-definitely-never-8824732 |title=7 things you DEFINITELY never knew about Sir Tom Jones|first=Nathan|last=Bevan|date=12 March 2015 |website= Walesonline.com| accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref><ref name= czone>{{cite news| url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9218515/Tom-Jones-Acting-is-harder-than-I-thought.-I-was-out-of-my-comfort-zone.html|title=Tom Jones: 'Acting is harder than I thought. I was out of my comfort zone'| first= Charlotte| last= Williamson|date=22 April 2012| accessdate= 14 December 2017| website= The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> In 1970 he received a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]] nomination for hosting the television series ''[[This Is Tom Jones]]''. In 2012, he played a role in an episode of ''[[Playhouse Presents]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/showbiz/jim-cartwright-how-tom-jones-2033197 |title= Jim Cartwright on how Tom Jones went from Sex Bomb to depressed ex-Teddy Boy| first= Nathan| last=Bevan|date=27 April 2012| website= Walesonline.co.uk|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref> Jones received a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best New Artist]] in 1966, an [[MTV Video Music Award]] in 1989, as well as two [[Brit Awards]]: Best British Male in 2000 and the Outstanding Contribution to Music award in 2003. Jones was appointed Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in 1998 and [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the United Kingdom|knighted]] by Queen [[Elizabeth II]] for services to music in 2005. Jones experienced a resurgence in notability in the 2010s due to his coaching role on the television talent show ''[[The Voice UK]]'' from 2012 (with the exception of 2016).<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite magazine| url= http://www.list.co.uk/article/39019-the-voice-line-up-revealed/ |title=The Voice line-up revealed |magazine=The List |date=28 November 2011 |accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nJones was born Thomas John Woodward<ref name=\"closeup\">{{cite book| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=x43jHZliCN0C&pg=PT74&dq=%22thomas+john+woodward%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCWoVChMIroKNgYqEyQIVxHwPCh21YAvO#v=onepage&q=%22thomas%20john%20woodward%22&f=false |first1= Lucy| last1=  Ellis| first2= Bryony |last2= Sutherland| title= Tom Jones Close Up| publisher= Omnibus Press| year= 2009| isbn= 978-0711975491}}</ref> at 57 Kingsland Terrace, [[Treforest]], [[Pontypridd]], in [[Glamorgan]], [[South Wales]].<ref>''Entry of Birth'', sub-district of Pontypridd in the County of Glamorgan</ref><ref>{{cite book| first= Robin| last= Eggar| title= Tom Jones \u2013 The Biography| page= 14}}</ref> His parents were Thomas Woodward (31 March 1910 \u2013 5 October 1981), a coal miner, and Freda Jones (30 December 1914 \u2013 7 February 2003).<ref name=\"closeup\" /> Three of his grandparents were of English origin: his paternal grandfather, James Woodward, was an ironmonger's haulier from [[Gloucestershire]], and his paternal grandmother, Anne Woodward, was from [[Wiltshire]]. His maternal grandfather, Albert Jones, was Welsh, and his maternal grandmother, Ada Jones, was born in Pontypridd, to parents from [[Somerset]] and Wiltshire.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/5490511/Sir-Tom-Jones-is-English.html |title=Sir Tom Jones 'is English' |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=10 June 2009|location=London |issn=0307-1235 |oclc=49632006 |accessdate=4 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nJones attended Wood Road Infants School, Wood Road Junior School and Pontypridd Central [[Secondary Modern School]].<ref>{{cite book|date=8 October 2015| first= Tom| last= Jones|isbn=978-0-7181-8068-3|title=Over the Top and Back: The Autobiography|publisher=Michael Joseph|page=25}}</ref> He began singing at an early age: he would regularly sing at family gatherings, weddings and in his school choir. Jones did not like school or sports, but gained confidence through his singing talent.<ref name=\"DIDiscs TJ\">{{cite episode |title=Desert Island Discs with Tom Jones |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00tx499 |series=Desert Island Discs | serieslink=Desert Island Discs |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]] |airdate=26 September 2010}}</ref> At 12 he was diagnosed with [[tuberculosis]]. Many years later he said: \"I spent two years in bed recovering. It was the worst time of my life.\" During convalescence, he could do little else but listen to music and draw.<ref name= \"closeup\" />{{rp|9\u201310}}\n\nJones's bluesy singing style developed out of the sound of American [[soul music]]. His early influences included [[blues music|blues]], [[R&B]] and [[rock and roll]] singers [[Little Richard]], [[Solomon Burke]], [[Jackie Wilson]], [[Brook Benton]], [[Elvis Presley]] and [[Jerry Lee Lewis]].<ref name=\"rollingstone2015\">Appleford, Steve [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/tom-jones-on-meeting-elvis-recording-with-bacharach-panty-magnet-phase-20151215 \"Tom Jones on Meeting Elvis, Recording With Bacharach, 'Panty Magnet' Phase\"]. ''Rolling Stone''. 17 December 2015. Retrieved 17 December 2015.</ref>\n\nIn March 1957 Jones married his high school girlfriend, Linda Trenchard, when they were expecting a child together, both aged 16. The couple's son, Mark, was born in the month following their wedding. To support his young family, Jones took a job working in a glove factory and was later employed in construction.\n\n==Career==\n===Rise to fame===\nJones's voice has been described as a \"full-throated, robust [[baritone]]\".<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> He became the frontman in 1963 for Tommy Scott and the Senators, a Welsh [[beat group]]. They soon gained a local following and reputation in [[South Wales]]. In 1964, the group recorded several solo tracks with producer [[Joe Meek]], who took them to various record labels, but they had little success. Later that year, [[Decca Records|Decca]] producer Peter Sullivan saw Tommy Scott and the Senators performing in a club and directed them to manager [[Phil Solomon (music executive)|Phil Solomon]], but the partnership was short-lived.\n\nThe group continued to play gigs at dance halls and [[working men's club]]s in South Wales. One night at the Top Hat in [[Cwmtillery]], Jones was spotted by [[Gordon Mills]], a London-based manager who also originally hailed from [[South Wales]]. Mills became Jones's manager, took the young singer to London, and also renamed him \"Tom Jones\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/music/sites/tom-jones/pages/biography_02.shtml |title=Music \u2013 Tom Jones \u2013 Tom Jones biography \u2013 part two |website=BBC Wales |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> to exploit the popularity of the Academy Award-winning [[Tom Jones (1963 film)|1963 film]].<ref>{{cite magazine| work= [[Life (magazine)|Life]] |title= They can always go home to MAM| date= 18 September 1970 | page= [https://books.google.com/books?id=8lUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA54&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-ICLUK2LFKrMmAWW1IHQDw&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=&f=false 54]| volume= 69| number= 12 |quote= Mills promptly changed the singer's name to Tom Jones, to exploit the popularity of the current film by that name, and for six months he and Tom and the accompanists lived off a loan Mills talked a bank into giving them.}}</ref>\n\nEventually, Mills got Jones a recording contract with [[Decca Records|Decca]]. His first single, \"Chills and Fever\", was released in late 1964. It did not chart, but the follow-up, \"[[It's Not Unusual]]\", became an international [[chart-topper|hit]] after offshore [[pirate radio]] station [[Radio Caroline]] promoted it. The following year was the most prominent of Jones's career, making him one of the most popular vocalists of the [[British Invasion]]. In early 1965, \"It's Not Unusual\" reached No. 1 in the United Kingdom and the top ten in the United States. During 1965, Mills secured a number of film themes for Jones to record, including the theme songs for the film ''[[What's New Pussycat?]]'' (written by [[Burt Bacharach]] and [[Hal David]]) and also for the [[James Bond]] film ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]''.<ref name=\"BioPart3\"/> Jones was also awarded the [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist]] in 1966.<ref name=\"Grammy\">{{cite magazine| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=5SgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA13&dq=tom+jones+grammy+award+best+new+artist&hl=en&sa=X&ei=dYaBT4GRLqWi0QXsqK2LBw&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=tom%20jones%20grammy%20award%20best%20new%20artist&f=false |title= Naras Champions of 1965| page= 12| work= Billboard | date= 26 March 1966| access-date= 8 April 2012}}</ref> In Hollywood, Jones met [[Elvis Presley]] for the first time; he recalls Presley singing his song as he walked towards him on set.\n\nIn 1966, Jones's popularity began to slip somewhat, causing Mills to reshape the singer's image into that of a [[crooner]]. Jones also began to sing material that appealed to a wider audience, such as the country hit \"[[Green, Green Grass of Home]]\". The strategy worked, and Jones returned to the top of the charts in the UK and began hitting the Top 40 again in the US. For the remainder of the decade, he scored a string of hits on both sides of the Atlantic, including \"[[I'll Never Fall in Love Again (Lonnie Donegan song)|I'll Never Fall in Love Again]]\", \"I'm Coming Home\", and \"Delilah\", each of which reached No. 2 in the UK chart.<ref name=\"Tom Jones Nostalgia Central\">{{cite web| url= http://www.nostalgiacentral.com/music/tomjones.htm | title= Tom Jones| website= nostalgiacentral.com |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060721100011/http://www.nostalgiacentral.com/music/tomjones.htm |archivedate= 21 July 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.classicbands.com/tomjones.html |title=Tom Jones |website=Classicbands.com |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Las Vegas===\nIn 1967, Jones performed in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] for the first time, at the [[Flamingo Las Vegas|Flamingo]].<ref name=\"BioPart3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/music/sites/tom-jones/pages/biography_03.shtml |title=Music \u2013 Tom Jones \u2013 Tom Jones biography \u2013 part three |website=BBC Wales |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> His performances and style of dress became part of his stage act, and increasingly featured his open, half-unbuttoned shirts and tight trousers. He soon chose to record less, instead concentrating on his lucrative club performances.\n\nJones and his idol [[Elvis Presley]] met in 1965 at the [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] film stage, when Elvis was filming ''[[Paradise, Hawaiian Style]]''.<ref name=\"rollingstone2015\"/><ref name=\"BioPart3\"/> They became good friends, spending more and more time together in Las Vegas and duetting until the early hours at Presley's private suite. The friendship endured until Presley's death in 1977.<ref name=\"BioPart3\"/> Jones's guitarist between 1969 and 1974 was [[Big Jim Sullivan]], who also met and formed a friendship with Presley.\n\nJones played in Las Vegas at least one week each year until 2011.\n\n===Television===\n[[File:Janis Joplin Tom Jones 1969.JPG|thumb|left|Jones duetting with [[Janis Joplin]] on the television programme ''[[This Is Tom Jones]]'' in 1969]]\nJones had an internationally successful television variety show titled ''[[This Is Tom Jones]]'' from 1969 to 1971.  The [[Associated Television]]-produced show was worth a reported {{US$|9000000|1971|about=yes|round=-5}} to Jones over three years.  It was broadcast by [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] in the UK and by the [[American Broadcasting Company]] in the US.  As a result of the show, Jones was nominated in 1970 for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|a \"best actor\" Golden Globe]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/music/sites/tom-jones/pages/this-is-tom-jones-dvd.shtml |publisher= BBC| place= Wales| title= ''This Is Tom Jones'' DVD review| date= | access-date= 5 January 2013}}</ref> From 1980 to 1981, he had a second television variety show, ''[[Tom Jones (TV series)|Tom Jones]]'', which was produced in [[Vancouver]], Canada, and lasted 24 episodes.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Both television shows were the subject of litigation with the original licence holder [[C/F International]].  {{As of|2004|12}}, C/F International was a secured judgment creditor of [[Classic World Productions]] and its principal, Darryl Payne, for approximately {{US$|1000000|2004|about=yes|round=-5}}, and was the principal secured creditor at the time of the subsequent bankruptcy filing by the company.  C/F International's action against Classic World Productions and owner Darryl Payne was based on unpaid [[royalty payment]]s from ''This Is Tom Jones''<ref>{{cite web|last=Hise |first=Micheal |url=http://www.tv.com/this-is-tom-jones/show/1146/summary.html |title=This is Tom Jones |website=TV.com |date=12 February 2008 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> and related recordings.<ref>[http://www.websupp.org/data/DNJ/2:01-cv-03624-94-DNJ.pdf C/F International Inc. v. Classic World Productions et al.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327115100/http://www.websupp.org/data/DNJ/2%3A01-cv-03624-94-DNJ.pdf |date=27 March 2009 }}, New Jersey District Court, Judgement of 16 February 2006 at page 2; Websupp.org.</ref> ''This Is Tom Jones'' is sold on DVD by [[Time Life]] rather than by Classic World Productions or C/F International.<ref>{{Cite web | url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110727053615/http://www.timelife.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/ProductDisplay?catalogId=10001&storeId=1001&langId=&top_category=90003&productId=211811 |title = Generic Error}}</ref>\n\nC/F International's rights to later Tom Jones material were also disputed.  In March 2007, Tom Jones and Tom Jones Enterprises sued C/F International to stop the company from licensing sound recordings made from the 1981 ''Tom Jones'' series.  It was contended that any rights that C/F International had to licence the ''Tom Jones'' show did not include the right to make and licence separate recordings of the performances on the show, and that any rights that C/F International had in the ''Tom Jones'' show no longer existed because of numerous breaches of contract.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storyCode=26492&sectioncode=1 |title=Tom Jones seeks injunction over recordings |magazine=Music Week |date=2 March 2007 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> Examples of contentious CDs are ''Live on the Tom Jones Show'', released in 2006, and ''Greatest Hits Live'', originally issued by C/F International in 1981 and later licensed to and issued by Prism Leisure Corporation as ''30 Greatest Hits \u2013 Live in Concert''.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.7digital.com/artists/various-artists/live-on-the-tom-jones-show/ |title= Live on The Tom Jones Show| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080124062521/http://www.7digital.com/artists/various-artists/live-on-the-tom-jones-show/ |archivedate=24 January 2008 | website= 7digital.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.discogs.com/Tom-Jones-30-Greatest-Hits-Live-In-Concert/release/10485850| website= Discogs.com| title= 30 Greatest Hits \u2013 Live in Concert| access-date= March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000URRAYC |title=Tom Jones \u2013 30 Greatest Hits/Live in Concert | website= Amazon.com |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 April 1970, [[CBS]] released the television special ''[[Raquel! (TV program)|Raquel!]]'' directed by [[David Winters (choreographer)|David Winters]], in which he was a guest. It starred [[Raquel Welch]], and other guests included [[Bob Hope]] and [[John Wayne]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0174154/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Raquel! (1970 TV Movie): Full Cast & Crew|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> It was filmed in London, Paris, [[Acapulco]], Mexico City, [[Yucatan]], [[Big Sur]], and Los Angeles and featured lavish production numbers. Welch and Jones combined musical and comedic talents on classic rock 'n' roll standards of the era.<ref name=\"HBJ\">{{cite book|title=Television: The Business Behind the Box.|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/televisionbusine00brow|chapter-url-access=registration|last=Brown|first=Les|publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich|year=1971|isbn=978-0-15-688440-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/televisionbusine00brow/page/187 187], 188|chapter= Raquel! }}</ref> Produced by Winters' company Winters/Rosen for CBS-TV, originally co-sponsored by [[Coca-Cola]] and [[Motorola]]. On the day of the premiere, the show received a 51% share on the National ARB Ratings and an impressive Overnight New York Nielsen Rating of 58% share.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://davidwinters.net/pic3.htm|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806025805/http://www.davidwinters.net/pic3.htm|archivedate=6 August 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=19 May 2011|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nightflight.com/happy-birthday-today-to-raquel-welch-her-1970-primetime-tv-special-will-melt-your-mind/|title=Happy Birthday today to Raquel Welch: Her 1970 primetime TV special will melt your mind!|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411013143/http://nightflight.com/happy-birthday-today-to-raquel-welch-her-1970-primetime-tv-special-will-melt-your-mind/|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=|access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Decline and resurgence===\n[[File:Celebrity Star Tom Jones Orpheum Theater Memphis TN.jpg|thumb|The star commemorating Jones at the [[Orpheum Theatre (Memphis, Tennessee)|Orpheum Theatre, Memphis]]]]\nIn the 1970s, Jones toured with the female singing groups [[Quiet Elegance]] and [[the Blossoms]] as his backing groups. He had a number of hit singles, including \"[[She's a Lady]]\", \"[[Till (song)|Till]]\", and \"[[The Young New Mexican Puppeteer]]\", but in the mid-1970s his popularity declined. He did, however, have a big hit in 1976 with \"[[Say You'll Stay Until Tomorrow]]\", which went to No. 1 on the US country chart, No. 15 on the Billboard Hot 100 and reached No. 40 on the UK Singles Chart.\n\nIn 1972, he reunited with director and choreographer [[David Winters (choreographer)|David Winters]] for the musical television special [[The Special London Bridge Special|''The Special London Bridge Special'']], co-starring [[Jennifer O'Neill]]. Others who participated as guests included [[The Carpenters]], [[Kirk Douglas]], [[Jonathan Winters]], [[Hermione Gingold]], [[Lorne Greene]], [[Chief Dan George]], [[Charlton Heston]], [[George Kirby]], [[Michael Landon]], [[Terry-Thomas]], [[Engelbert Humperdinck (singer)|Engelbert Humperdinck]], [[Elliott Gould]], [[Merle Park]], and [[Rudolf Nureyev]].<ref name=\"closeup\" /><ref>{{Cite news|date=7 May 1972|title=Introducing London Bridge Special| journal= [[The Anniston Star]] |volume= 93 |pages= 48|via= Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Indian chief in Disney tribe|journal= [[The Herald-News]] |volume=103|pages=39|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976, Jones was set to make his film debut in the film ''Yockowald'', in which he was to play a [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] assassin. The film was shelved after the production ran out of money three weeks into filming.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/7-things-you-definitely-never-8824732|title=7 things you DEFINITELY never knew about Sir Tom Jones |first= Nathan |last= Bevan |date=12 March 2015 |website= Walesonline.co.uk|accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979, Jones made his acting debut in ''[[Pleasure Cove]]'', an [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television film which was an unsuccessful pilot for a potential television series along the lines of ''[[Love Boat]]'' and ''[[Fantasy Island]]''. In the film, he played a suave conman named Raymond Gordon staying at the holiday island resort of the title. His co-stars in the film included [[Constance Forslund]], [[Tanya Roberts]] and [[David Hasselhoff]].<ref name= \"closeup\" />{{rp|326}} He guest-starred in an episode of ''[[Fantasy Island]]'' in 1984.\n\nIn the early 1980s, Jones started to record country music. From 1980 to 1986, he had nine songs in the US country top 40, yet failed to crack the top 100 in the UK or the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"Tom Jones Discography\">{{cite web| url= http://www.tomjonesonline.com/tom-jones-discography.php| title= Discography| website= tomjonesonline.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100221021950/http://www.tomjonesonline.com/tom-jones-discography.php |archivedate=21 February 2010 | access-date= }}</ref> Jones's manager Gordon Mills died of cancer on 29 July 1986, and Jones's son Mark became his manager.<ref name= \"closeup\" />{{rp|271, 275}}\n\nIn 1987, Tom Jones re-entered the singles chart with \"[[Matador (English musical)|A Boy From Nowhere]]\", which went to No. 2 in the UK. The following year, he covered [[Prince (musician)|Prince]]'s \"[[Kiss (Tom Jones song)|Kiss]]\" with [[Art of Noise]]. The song reached No. 5 in the UK and No. 31 in the US. The video for \"Kiss\" was played frequently on MTV and [[VH1]], and won the [[MTV Video Music Award \u2013 Breakthrough Video|MTV Video Music Award for Breakthrough Video]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1989/mtvvmas.htm |title=1989 MTV Video Music Awards |publisher=Rock on the Net |date=6 September 1989 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nJones received a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in 1989, located at 6608 [[Hollywood Boulevard]], Los Angeles, California, in front of [[Frederick's of Hollywood]]. In 1992, he made his first appearance at the UK's [[Glastonbury Festival]], and in 1993 he appeared as himself in episodes of two popular US sitcoms, ''[[The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air]]'' and ''[[The Simpsons]]''.\n\nJones signed with [[Interscope Records]] in 1993 and released the album ''The Lead And How To Swing It''. The first single, \"If I Only Knew\", went to No. 11 in the UK.<ref name=\"Tom Jones Discography\"/> Jones performed the song at the [[1994 MTV Europe Music Awards]], for which he also served as host. In 1997, Jones contributed to the soundtrack for the UK comedy film ''[[The Full Monty]]'', recording \"[[You Can Leave Your Hat On]]\".<ref>{{cite web| first= Robert |last= Carlyle |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-full-monty-original-soundtrack-r307874 |title=The Full Monty [Original Soundtrack&#93; \u2013 Original Soundtrack &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date=12 August 1997 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, he appeared as himself in [[Tim Burton]]'s ensemble science-fiction comedy film ''[[Mars Attacks!]]''. A scene in the film features Jones performing on stage when aliens attack and he manages to escape with a gun.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/20-knew-ol'-tom-jones-60-singer-surprise-star-mars-attacks-article-1.741534|title=20 Things you Never Knew About Ol Tom Jones is Surprise Star of Mars Attacks |website=Daily News|location=New York|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Jones released the album ''[[Reload (Tom Jones album)|Reload]]'', a collection of cover duets with artists such as [[the Cardigans]], [[Natalie Imbruglia]], [[Cerys Matthews]], [[Van Morrison]], [[Mousse T]], [[Portishead (band)|Portishead]], [[Stereophonics]] and [[Robbie Williams]]. The album went to No. 1 in the UK and sold over 4 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wBeEDJhw110C&pg=PA28&lpg=PA28&dq=tom+jones+reload+4+million+worldwide#v=onepage&q=tom%20jones%20reload%204%20million%20worldwide&f=false|title=Howie Richmond Hitmaker Award: Tom Jones|magazine=Billboard|page=28|date=20 June 2009|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref> Five singles from ''Reload'' charted in the UK top 40.<ref name=\"Tom Jones Discography\"/><ref name=\"Tom Jones Bio\">{{cite web| website= yuddy.com| url= http://www.yuddy.com/celebrity/tom-jones/bio| title= Tom Jones Biography |date= | access-date= |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100112223520/http://www.yuddy.com/celebrity/tom-jones/bio |archivedate=12 January 2010 }}</ref> The single \"[[Sex Bomb (song)|Sex Bomb]]\" was released in early 2000 and became the album's biggest single, reaching No. 3 in the UK Singles Chart.\n\n===Into the 21st century===\nUS President [[Bill Clinton]] invited Jones to perform on New Year's Eve at the 2000 millennium celebrations in Washington DC. In 2000, Jones garnered a number of honours for his work, including a [[BRIT Awards|BRIT Award]] for Best British Male.<ref name=\"Brits\">[http://www.brits.co.uk/artist/tom-jone ]{{Dead link|date=October 2015}}</ref> He was also hired as the new voice of Australia's [[National Rugby League]], singing in an advertisement to market the 2000 season.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mealey |first=Rachel| website= abc.net.au |title=Tom Jones the new voice of NRL |location=Australia  |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=29 January 2000 |url= http://www.abc.net.au/am/stories/s96345.htm |accessdate=3 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Jones released the album ''[[Mr. Jones (Tom Jones album)|Mr. Jones]]'', which was produced by Haitian-American rapper [[Wyclef Jean]]. The album and the first single, \"Tom Jones International\", were top 40 hits in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B00006J9NE |title=Mr Jones: Amazon.co.uk: Music |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nJones received the Brit Award for Outstanding Contribution to Music in 2003.<ref name=\"Brits\"/> The following year, he teamed up with pianist [[Jools Holland]] and released ''Tom Jones & Jools Holland'', a roots rock 'n' roll album. It peaked at No. 5 in the UK.<ref name=\"Tom Jones Discography\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B0002Y9TRO |title=Tom Jones & Jools Holland| website= Amazon.com |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 May 2005, in celebration of his upcoming 65th birthday, Jones returned to his homeland to perform a concert in [[Ynysangharad Park]], Pontypridd before an audience of about 20,000. This was his first performance in Pontypridd since 1964.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/south_east/4590941.stm |title=Home town triumph for Tom Jones |date=29 May 2005 |publisher=BBC News   |accessdate=23 November 2011}}</ref> That same year, the BBC reported that Jones was Wales's wealthiest entertainer, having amassed a [[Wealth|fortune]] of \u00a3175,000,000.<ref>{{cite news |date=2 April 2005 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/4401733.stm |title=Financier heads Welsh rich list |publisher=BBC News  |accessdate=12 February 2008}}</ref> Jones collaborated with Australian pop singer [[John Farnham]] in 2005 and released the live album ''[[John Farnham & Tom Jones \u2013 Together in Concert]]''. The following year, Jones worked with [[Chicane (recording artist)|Chicane]] and released the dance track \"[[Stoned in Love]]\", which went to No. 7 in the UK Singles Chart.<ref name=\"Tom Jones Discography\"/>\n\nJones, who had been awarded an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in 1999, was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] by Queen [[Elizabeth II]] in 2006 at [[Buckingham Palace]] for his services to music.<ref name=\"BBC2006\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/4853732.stm| title=Tom Jones collects his knighthood|publisher=BBC News | date=29 March 2006| accessdate=29 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/tom-jones |title=Tom Jones  |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 June 2012 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> After receiving a knighthood, Jones stated: \"When you first come into show business and get a hit record, it is the start of something. As time goes by it just gets better. This is the best thing I have had. It's a wonderful feeling, a heady feeling.\"<ref name=\"BBC2006\"/>\n\n===2007\u20132009===\nOn 1 July 2007, Jones was among the artists who performed at [[Wembley Stadium]] at the [[Concert for Diana]], joined on stage by guitarist [[Joe Perry (musician)|Joe Perry]] of [[Aerosmith]] and soul singer [[Joss Stone]]. In addition to performing some of his own songs, the group covered the [[Arctic Monkeys]] song, \"[[I Bet You Look Good on the Dancefloor]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.covermesongs.com/2010/08/tom-jones-w-joe-perry-i-bet-you-look-good-on-the-dancefloor.html |title=Song of the Day: Tom Jones w/ Joe Perry, \"I Bet You Look Good on the Dancefloor\" (Arctic Monkeys cover) \u00bb Cover Me |website=Covermesongs.com |date=27 August 2010 |accessdate=14 July 2011}}</ref> A boxing fan, Jones has performed national anthems before a number of boxing matches. He sang \"[[God Save the Queen]]\", the national anthem of the United Kingdom, before the [[Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Ricky Hatton|Floyd Mayweather-Ricky Hatton fight]] in 2007; he sang \"[[Hen Wlad Fy Nhadau]]\", the Welsh national anthem, at the [[Bernard Hopkins vs. Joe Calzaghe|Bernard Hopkins-Joe Calzaghe fight]] between fellow Welshman [[Joe Calzaghe]] and [[Bernard Hopkins]] in 2008; and he sang \"God Save the Queen\" before the [[Manny Pacquiao vs. Ricky Hatton|Manny Pacquiao-Ricky Hatton fight]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/more_sport/article3736265.ece|title=The Times & The Sunday Times|website=The Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/more_sport/article3023565.ece |title=The Times |work=The Times |date=28 September 2015 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.eastsideboxing.com/news.php?p=19671&more=1]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601161715/http://www.eastsideboxing.com/news.php?p=19671&more=1 |date=1 June 2009 }}</ref>\n[[File:Tom Jones Hampton Court Palace 2007.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Performing at [[Hampton Court Palace]] in London, 2007]]\n\nIn 2008, he released ''24 Hours'' on [[S-Curve Records]], his first album of new material to be issued in the United States for over 15 years. Jones, who was still performing over 200 dates a year as he approached his seventieth birthday, set out on a world tour to promote the album. \"The fire is still in me. Not to be an oldie, but a goodie. I want to be a contender\", Jones said.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7620450.stm |title=Sir Tom Jones eyes fresh comeback |publisher=BBC News  |date=17 September 2008 |accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Russell |first=Gwen |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B001G5SDA2 |title=24 Hours: Tom Jones: Music |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=14 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tomjones.com/news/santiago-takes-its-hat-off-to-tom-jones-santiago-times-review/ |title=Santiago takes its hat off to Tom Jones \u2013 Santiago Times Review |publisher=Tom Jones |accessdate=12 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016072640/http://www.tomjones.com/news/santiago-takes-its-hat-off-to-tom-jones-santiago-times-review/ |archive-date=16 October 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Also in 2008, Jones was inducted into the Hit Parade Hall of Fame. On 16 November 2008, he was invited to perform on BBC's ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''; he performed the debut single from ''24 Hours'', \"If He Should Ever Leave You\", which was named the ninth-best song of 2008 by [[Spinner (web site)|Spinner]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spinner.com/2008/12/12/best-songs-of-2008-no-9 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306003200/http://www.spinner.com/2008/12/12/best-songs-of-2008-no-9 |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 March 2012 |title=Best Songs of 2008: No. 9 |work=Spinner |accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/8299511.stm |title=In conversation with Sir Tom  |publisher=BBC News  |date=9 October 2009 |accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|I39LiZjqDes|\"Tom Jones 'If He Should Ever Leave You' Strictly Come Dancing\"}}</ref> One of the songs from ''24 Hours'', \"Give a Little Love\", would later be featured in the first trailer for the 2010 comedy film, ''[[Little Fockers]]''.\n\nIn February 2009, Jones appeared in an exclusive [[Take-Away Show]] with [[Vincent Moon]], performing three songs live in front of a camera in a New York hotel room.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blogotheque.net/Tom-Jones |title=Tom Jones&nbsp;\u2013 LA BLOGOTHEQUE |website=Blogotheque.net |accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref> In March 2009, Jones went to the top of the UK Music Charts for the third time in his career with a cover of \"[[Islands in the Stream (song)|Islands in the Stream]]\", sung with [[Ruth Jones (actress)|Ruth Jones]], [[Rob Brydon]] and [[Robin Gibb]], who co-wrote the original with his brothers [[Barry Gibb|Barry]] and [[Maurice Gibb|Maurice]]. The record, which was inspired by the song's having featured in the BBC's hit sitcom ''[[Gavin & Stacey]]'', was released in aid of [[Comic Relief]] and reached No. 1 in March 2009.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/269201/u2-comic-relief-top-uk-charts |title=U2, Comic Relief Top U.K. Charts |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2010\u2013present===\n[[File:Tom Jones concert.jpg|thumb|200px|Jones at [[House of Blues]], [[Anaheim, California|Anaheim]], 2009]]\nJones's album ''[[Praise & Blame]]'' was released on 26 July 2010. The album, consisting primarily of gospel and blues songs, included covers of songs by [[Bob Dylan]], [[John Lee Hooker]] and [[Billy Joe Shaver]], and featured guest musicians such as [[Booker T. Jones|Booker T.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/tom-jones/51098 |title=Tom Jones covering Bob Dylan, John Lee Hooker on new album |work=NME |date=17 May 2010 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Kitty |last=Empire |title=Tom Jones: Praise & Blame |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jul/25/tom-jones-praise-blame-review |date=24 July 2010 |accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 June 2010, which was Jones's seventieth birthday, the single \"Burning Hell\", a cover of the John Lee Hooker song from the ''Praise & Blame'' album, was released. In July 2010, it was reported that David Sharpe, vice-president of [[Island Records]] (to whom Jones had moved, from [[EMI]], for \u00a31.5m in October 2009), had emailed colleagues demanding that they \"pull back this project immediately or get my money back\" and asking if the spiritually themed record had been a \"sick joke\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/7870995/Tom-Joness-record-boss-complains-his-new-album-sounds-like-hymns.html |title=Tom Jones's record boss complains his new album sounds like hymns |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> Jones later strongly criticised Sharpe and said that he was furious about the leaked email.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2010/07/10/tom-jones-furious-at-record-company-boss-s-comments-91466-26823038/ |title=Tom Jones furious at record company boss's comments |work=Wales Online |date= 9 July 2010|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Jones appeared on the penultimate episode of ''[[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]'' and performed \"Burning Hell\". In August 2010, ''Praise & Blame'' debuted at No. 2 on the UK album chart.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/latest/2010/08/01/eminem-beats-tom-jones-to-no-1-spot-115875-22457228/ | title = Eminem beats Tom Jones to No 1 spot | date = 1 August 2010 | newspaper = Mirror | location = London | accessdate =24 August 2010}}</ref> By 2010 Jones had sold a total of over 100 million records.<ref name=\"3News_142546\">{{cite news |url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Tom-Jones-Its-not-unusual-no/tabid/728/articleID/142546/Default.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929131157/http://www.3news.co.nz/Tom-Jones-Its-not-unusual-no/tabid/728/articleID/142546/Default.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 September 2012 |title=Tom Jones: 'It's not unusual, no' |date=18 February 2010 |work=[[3 News]] |accessdate=23 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 September 2010, Jones performed for an audience of 50,000 at the ''[[Help for Heroes]]'' charity concert at [[Twickenham Stadium]] performing \"[[Sister Rosetta Tharpe|Strange Things Are Happening Every Day]]\" and his hit \"[[Green, Green Grass of Home]]\". On 22 September, Jones appeared on the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' at the [[Ed Sullivan Theater]] in New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvmaze.com/episodes/27347/the-late-show-with-david-letterman-2010-09-22-joaquin-phoenix-tom-jones|title=Joaquin Phoenix, Tom Jones \u2013 The Late Show with David Letterman 2010-09-22|publisher=TVmaze|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, Jones appeared as a guest vocalist on the debut album ''[[Let Them Talk (Hugh Laurie album)|Let Them Talk]]'' by [[Hugh Laurie]]. On 15 May 2011, he appeared alongside Laurie in the UK [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] series ''Perspectives'', singing music from the album in [[New Orleans]].<ref>[http://www.itv.com/perspectives/essays/hugh-laurie/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://archive.today/20130103095138/http://www.itv.com/perspectives/essays/hugh-laurie/ |date=3 January 2013 }}</ref> On 25 May 2011, he appeared on '' [[American Idol (season 10)|American Idol]] '' after a medley of his hits performed by the American Idol \"Top 13\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Herndon |first=Jessica |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20497722,00.html |title=Tom Jones, Tony Bennett, Tim McGraw Perform at Idol Finale |work=People  |date=26 May 2011 |accessdate=14 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nJones released a single on 19 March 2012, produced by former [[White Stripes]] frontman [[Jack White (musician)|Jack White]], called ''Evil''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/jack-white/61946 |title=Hear Jack White's 'Evil' collaboration with Tom Jones |website=NME |date=9 February 2012 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The single was first made available through independent record shops in 7\" vinyl format on 5 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecmuwebsite.com/article/tom-jones-and-jack-white-single-to-be-sold-nationwide/ |title=Tom Jones and Jack White single to be sold nationwide |work=Thecmuwebsite.com |date=27 February 2012 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> An exclusive [[Unusual types of gramophone records|three-coloured vinyl]] was also sold at only one shop \u2013 [[Spillers Records]] in [[Cardiff]]. The shop, from which Jones bought records as a schoolboy in the 1950s and early 1960s, was founded in 1894 and is listed in ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' as the oldest record shop in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/9100881/Tom-Jones-single-to-be-sold-in-one-shop-only.html|title=Tom Jones single to be sold in one shop only|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=23 February 2012|accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, Jones became a coach on the BBC talent show ''[[The Voice UK]]''.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> Jones was joined by [[will.i.am]], [[Jessie J]] and [[Danny O'Donoghue]]. He mentored [[Leanne Mitchell]] to win the first series. Jones returned to coach in 2013, 2014 and 2015. In August 2015, it was announced that Jones's contract with the show would not be renewed and that he would be replaced by [[Boy George]]. Jones criticised BBC executives for \"sub-standard behaviour\", having not consulted with him and informing him only 24 hours before the official announcement.<ref>{{cite news|author=Rose Troup Buchanan |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/tom-jones-dropped-from-the-voice-singer-criticises-bbc-executives-for-substandard-behaviour-after-hes-axed-from-fifth-series-10456948.html |title=Tom Jones dropped from The Voice: Singer criticises 'BBC executives' for 'sub-standard behaviour' after he's axed from fifth series |work=[[The Independent]] |date=15 August 2015 |accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, Jones released the album ''Spirit in the Room'' on [[Island Records]]/[[Universal Music]]. The track listing included covers of songs by [[Paul McCartney]], [[Paul Simon]], [[Leonard Cohen]] and [[Richard and Linda Thompson]], [[Blind Willie Johnson]], [[Tom Waits]] and [[the Low Anthem]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/may/20/tom-jones-spirit-room-review?newsfeed=true |title=Tom Jones: Spirit in the Room |work=The Guardian |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, he starred in a one-off television drama titled \"King of the Teds\" which aired on [[Sky Arts]] as part of a series of standalone teleplays for ''[[Playhouse Presents]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9244325/King-of-the-Teds-Sky-Arts-review.html|title=King of the Teds, Sky Arts, review|first=Rachel|last=Ward|date=4 May 2012|accessdate=14 December 2017|website=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 June 2012, Jones performed at the Queen's [[Diamond Jubilee Concert]] in front of [[Buckingham Palace]], singing \"Delilah\" and \"[[Mama Told Me Not to Come]]\".{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn 18 August 2012, Jones performed a fifty-minute set at the [[V Festival]]\u2019s Weston Park site in [[Staffordshire]].<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/v-festival-liveblog-gossip-pictures-1264340 \"Liveblog: Relive our V Festival weekend, all of the gossip, pictures and video from the star-studded VIP area\"]. ''Daily Mirror''. Retrieved 22 August 2012.</ref> On 9 September 2012, Jones headlined at [[BBC Radio 2]]'s Live in Hyde Park festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/e68v4f/acts/ajdg9r |title=Radio 2 Live in Hyde Park \u2013 2012 \u2013 Acts \u2013 Sir Tom Jones |publisher=BBC |date=9 September 1015 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, Jones opened for [[Morrissey]] at a special show in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Tom Jones and Sir Cliff Richard to support Morrissey at major US shows|url=https://www.nme.com/news/morrissey/75468|accessdate=15 February 2014|newspaper=[[NME]]|date=13 February 2014}}</ref> On 27 September 2014, Jones performed at the [[Australian Football League]]'s pre-game entertainment for the [[2014 AFL Grand Final|2014 Grand Final]] along with [[Ed Sheeran]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2014-09-01/tom-jones-to-star-on-gf-stage |title=What's news, pussycat? Tom Jones, Ed Sheeran to star on GF stage |website=AFL.com.au |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Jones announced the long-awaited release of his album ''[[Long Lost Suitcase]]'', on 9 October, through Virgin/EMI. The album is the third in a trilogy of albums, following ''Praise & Blame'' (2010) and ''Spirit in the Room'' (2012). The album's track titles are interwoven into the chapters of his autobiography ''Over the Top and Back'' released at the same time. It was produced by [[Ethan Johns]] and the diverse range of compositions includes songs from [[Gillian Welch]], [[the Rolling Stones]], [[Hank Williams]] and [[the Milk Carton Kids]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.music-news.com/news/UK/91959/Read |title=Tom Jones announces new album |publisher=Music-News.com |date=2 September 2015 |accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, Jones appeared alongside [[Rob Brydon]] in a special 90-minute show, from the [[Wembley Arena|SSE Arena, Wembley]], for BBC's [[Children in Need]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06pf7sb|title=Tom Jones & Rob Brydon: One Big Night for Children in Need|work=BBC One|date=12 November 2015|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he appeared on the BBC's ''[[Jools' Annual Hootenanny]]'', broadcast on New Year's Eve, on which he duetted with [[Paul Weller]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01pk3kf|title=Jools' Annual Hootenanny, 2015/16|work=[[BBC Two]]|date=31 December 2015|accessdate=2 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he returned to ''The Voice'' as a coach for [[The Voice UK (series 6)|series 6]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-01-09/who-is-tom-jones-the-voice-uk-coach-profile|title=Who is The Voice UK 2017 judge Tom Jones?|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=9 January 2017|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he embarked on a live summer tour, which was planned to run from 1 May to 11 August.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bestclassicbands.com/tom-jones-2018-tour-dates-4-23-18/|title=Tom Jones Adds 2018 Tour Dates \u2013 Best Classic Bands|date=11 June 2015|work=Best Classic Bands|access-date=31 July 2018}}</ref> In July, however, many shows were cancelled due to sickness or bad weather.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/news/sir-tom-jones-78-makes-triumphant-return-to-the-stage-after-bacterial-infection-and-thunderstorms-forced-him-to-miss-six-shows/ar-BBLhslV|title=Sir Tom Jones, 78, makes triumphant return to the stage... after bacterial infection and thunderstorms forced him to miss SIX shows|publisher=MSN|access-date=31 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731123522/https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/news/sir-tom-jones-78-makes-triumphant-return-to-the-stage-after-bacterial-infection-and-thunderstorms-forced-him-to-miss-six-shows/ar-BBLhslV|archive-date=31 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-44885944|title=Tom Jones postpones show due to illness|date=19 July 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 June 2019 ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Jones among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=28 June 2019 |date=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJones was married to Linda (born 1941 as Melinda Rose Trenchard) from 2 March 1957 until her death on 10 April 2016.<ref>{{cite book|date=8 October 2015|author=Tom Jones|isbn=978-0-7181-8068-3|title=Over the Top and Back: The Autobiography|publisher=Michael Joseph|pages=63\u201364}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/tom-jones-wife-linda-dies-11167791#rlabs=1%20p$7|title=Tom Jones' wife Linda dies after \"short but fierce\" battle with cancer|author=Mears, Tyler|date=11 April 2016|work=Wales Online|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> They stayed married despite his many well-publicised [[infidelity|infidelities]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/tom-jones-i-still-love-2125116|title=Tom Jones 'I still love Linda'|work=[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]|date=21 February 2009|accessdate=2 January 2016}}</ref> The couple had one son, Mark Woodward (born 1957).\n\nJones has stated that he had sex with up to 250 groupies a year at the height of his fame.<ref name= czone /> His [[philandering]] once led Linda to assault him. Jones had [[affair]]s with well-known women, including [[Mary Wilson (singer)|Mary Wilson]] of [[the Supremes]], TV host [[Charlotte Laws]]<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.sabado.pt/vida/detalhe/charlotte_fura_festas_e_vingadora.html|title=Charlotte Laws: fura-festas e vingadora |website= Sabado.pt |accessdate= 12 October 2015}}</ref> and former Miss World [[Marjorie Wallace]].<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/the-voice-judge-tom-jones-affair-777978 |title= Tom Jones, the Miss World who stole his heart and the faithful wife who wrested it back| first= Dominic |last= Herbert| work= Daily Mirror| date= 1 April 2012| access-date= 12 April 2012}}</ref> In a 2008 interview with ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' magazine, [[Cassandra Peterson]] (better known as ''Elvira, Mistress of the Dark'') revealed she lost her [[virginity]] to Jones.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2008/07/09/elvira_was_deflowered_by_tom_jones_neede |title=Elvira Was Deflowered By Tom Jones; Needed Stitches |date=9 July 2008 |accessdate=3 October 2011 |magazine=StarPulse.com |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080712184407/http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2008/07/09/elvira_was_deflowered_by_tom_jones_neede |archivedate= 12 July 2008 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nOne affair resulted in the birth of a son. In October 1987, while on tour in the US, Jones had a brief relationship with model Katherine Berkery, who then discovered she was pregnant. After a legal battle that included [[DNA]] [[paternity test|testing]], a United States court ruled in 1989 that Jones was the boy's father. Jones denied the court's findings, until finally, in 2008, he admitted they were true. He has shown no interest in meeting his son, Jonathan Berkery.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2008/12/14/tom-jones-admits-he-is-father-of-us-singer-91466-22470948|title=Tom Jones admits he is father of US singer|work=Wales Online|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|election of a Labour government in 1974]], Jones became a [[tax exile]] to avoid a 98 per cent income tax.<ref name=\"closeup\"/> In June 1976, he purchased the red-brick mansion at [[363 Copa De Oro Road]] in the [[East Gate Bel Air, Los Angeles|East Gate Old Bel Air in Los Angeles]] from [[Dean Martin]] for $500,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/welsh-homes/8000-semi-6m-bel-air-8631385|title=From the \u00a38,000 semi to $6m Bel Air mansion, inside the houses Sir Tom Jones has called home|work=Wales Online|date=12 February 2015|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> He sold it to [[Nicolas Cage]] in 1998 for a reported $6.469&nbsp;million. In 2009, after 35 years in the US, Jones said that he and his wife were planning to move back to the UK. \"I've had a great time living in Los Angeles\", Jones said, \"but after all these years, we think now is the time to move home\".<ref name=\"Tom Jones Bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/a163139/tom-jones-moving-back-to-britain.html|title=Tom Jones 'moving back to Britain'|work=Digital Spy|date=2 July 2009|accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015 his autobiography, ''Over the Top and Back: The Autobiography'', was published by [[Michael Joseph (publisher)|Michael Joseph]].<ref>{{cite book|date=8 October 2015| first= Tom |last= Jones|isbn=978-0-7181-8068-3|title=Over the Top and Back: The Autobiography| publisher= Michael Joseph}}</ref> Reviewing the book in the ''[[Daily Express]]'', Clair Woodward said, \"In the tradition of so many autobiographies these days, Tom Jones's doesn't tell you what you really want to hear. ... What you are left with is a riotously enjoyable story of Jones 'The Voice' which nicely doubles as the story of British pop and light entertainment from the Sixties onwards.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Woodward |first=Clair |url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/books/609200/Over-The-Top-And-Back-The-Autobiography-Sir-Tom-Jones-Leading-Dictator-book-review |title=Book reviews: Over The Top And Back: The Autobiography |work=Daily Express|date=2 October 2015|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nLinda, Lady Woodward, died on 10 April 2016 at [[Cedars-Sinai Medical Center|Cedars Sinai Hospital]] in Los Angeles, after a \"short but fierce\" battle with cancer, with Jones cancelling concerts at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-36015366|title=Sir Tom Jones's wife Lady Melinda Rose Woodward dies|publisher=BBC News|date=11 April 2016|accessdate=28 May 2016}}</ref> After her death, Jones sold their Los Angeles mansion and its contents, apart from treasured photos, and moved back to the UK. He resides in a flat in London, as she suggested.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/901147/tom-jones-wife-linda-lung-cancer-dying-wish-LA-home-london-the-voice-UK| title= Sir Tom Jones confesses he moved to London to fulfil his late wife's dying wish| first= Julia| last= Kuttner| date= January 7, 2018 |website= express.co.uk| publisher= | access-date= March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural influence==\n[[Space (English band)|Space]] and [[Cerys Matthews]] released \"[[The Ballad of Tom Jones]]\", a song about a fighting couple who are calmed down by listening to Jones's music on the radio. The song reached No. 4 in the UK in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spacetheband.com/discography/singles/the-ballad-of-tom-jones|title=The Ballad of Tom Jones the Single by Space \u2013 Discography|publisher=Space the Band|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nA new musical, ''Tom: A Story of Tom Jones'', based on the singer's life and recordings, produced by Theatr na n\u00d3g, opened at the [[Wales Millennium Centre]] in March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/tomthemusical/photos/a.595559490546690/672986666137305/?type=3&theater|title=Tom the Musical Facebook photo|work=Facebook|access-date=27 August 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=March 2020}}</ref> Reviewing the show for ''[[The Stage]]'', Mark Shenton wrote:\n\n<blockquote>...the show itself, written by Mike James and directed by Geinor Styles, is a more humdrum\u2014while hummable\u2014affair than its star and subject deserves. In the familiar jukebox musical style of shows like [[Jersey Boys]] and [[Beautiful: The Carole King Musical|Beautiful]], \"A Story of Tom Jones\" charts the behind-the-scenes rise to fame of a pop star, but without the craft or polish.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shenton|first=Mark|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/2016/tom-story-tom-jones-musical-review-wales-millennium-centre-cardiff-lacks-dramatic-meat|title=Tom: A Story of Tom Jones, the Musical review at Wales Millennium Centre, Cardiff \u2013 'lacks dramatic meat'|website=The Stage |date=10 March 2016|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nSimilar to [[Elvis Presley]] with his [[Elvis impersonator|impersonators]], Tom Jones has his share of [[Tom Jones impersonator|imitators]] around the world. These are performers who either sound like him or imitate his act.<ref>''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', 11 April 2018 \u2013 [https://www.latimes.com/sports/hockey/la-sp-kings-golden-knights-elliott-20180411-story.html Golden Knights give Vegas a real sense of community]</ref><ref>''Billboard'', 9 May 1998 \u2013 [https://books.google.com/books?id=UQ0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA60 Page 60 Newsmakers, '''Now The Real Thing.''']</ref><ref>''[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]'', Saturday, 7 July 2007 \u2013 [https://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2007/07/07/warren-makes-time-for-grandson/ Warren makes time for grandson by Stuart Michael]</ref>\n\nIn the 2006 film ''[[Flushed Away]]'', the main character Roddy is mistaken for Tom Jones by another character while Roddy performs \"[[She's a Lady]]\". Jones's song, \"[[What's New Pussycat? (song)|What's New Pussycat?]]\", is played during the ending credits.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nIn the video game ''[[Team Fortress 2]]'', one of the playable characters the Scout is a collector of Tom Jones' merchandise, and upon his death in the comics one of the other characters, the Spy falsely convinces him that Tom Jones is in fact his father. Tom Jones is also depicted using the phrase \"What's new pussycat?\" several times.<ref>''[[Team Fortress 2]]'', 10 January 2017 \u2013 [http://www.teamfortress.com/tf06_thenakedandthedead/ TF Comics 6: The Naked and the Dead]</ref>\n\n==Selected discography==\n{{Main|Tom Jones discography}}\n{{div col}}\n*''[[Along Came Jones (album)|Along Came Jones]]'' (1965)\n*''[[What's New Pussycat? (Tom Jones album)|What's New Pussycat?]]'' (1965)\n*''[[A-tom-ic Jones]]'' (1966)\n*''[[From the Heart (Tom Jones album)|From the Heart]]'' (1966)\n*''[[Green, Green Grass of Home (album)|Green, Green Grass of Home]]'' (1967)\n*''[[Delilah (Tom Jones album)|Delilah]]'' (1968)\n*''[[Help Yourself (Tom Jones album)|Help Yourself]]'' (1968)\n*''[[Reload (Tom Jones album)|Reload]]'' (1999)\n*''[[Mr. Jones (Tom Jones album)|Mr. Jones]]'' (2002)\n*''Tom Jones & Jools Holland'' {{small|(with [[Jools Holland]])}} (2004)\n*''24 Hours'' (2008)\n*''[[Praise & Blame]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Spirit in the Room]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Long Lost Suitcase]]'' (2015)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Compositions==\nJones wrote or co-wrote the following songs: \"And I Tell the Sea\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/chronicles-mw0000174224|title=Chronicles \u2013 Tom Jones|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref> \"Looking Out My Window\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/looking-out-my-window-mt0013407112|title=Looking Out My Window \u2013 Tom Jones|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref> \"Feel the Rain\"  from the 2002 ''[[Mr. Jones (Tom Jones album)|Mr. Jones]]'' album,<ref name=\"mrjones\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/mr-jones-mw0000457994|title=Mr. Jones \u2013 Tom Jones|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=4 August 2013}}</ref> \"Jezebel\",<ref name=\"mrjones\"/> \"The Letter\",<ref name=\"mrjones\"/> \"Younger Days\",<ref name=\"mrjones\"/> \"Tom Jones International\",<ref name=\"mrjones\"/> \"Holiday\",<ref name=\"mrjones\"/> \"The Road\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/3276580/Sir-Tom-Jones-writes-love-song-for-wife-Linda.html|title=Sir Tom Jones writes love song for wife Linda|work=The Telegraph|date=29 October 2008|accessdate=4 August 2013|last1=Irvine|first1=Chris}}</ref> \"24 Hours\",<ref name=\"24h\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/24-hours-mw0000802615|title=24 Hours \u2013 Tom Jones|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=4 August 2013}}</ref> \"Seasons\",<ref name=\"24h\"/> \"We Got Love\",<ref name=\"24h\"/> \"Seen That Face\",<ref name=\"24h\"/> \"Give a Little Love\",<ref name=\"24h\"/> \"If He Should Ever Leave You\",<ref name=\"24h\"/> \"Whatever it Takes\",<ref name=\"mrjones\"/> and \"Traveling Shoes\" from the 2012 album ''[[Spirit in the Room]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/spirit-in-the-room-mw0002348561|title=Spirit in the Room \u2013 Tom Jones|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=4 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!| Year\n!| Title\n!| Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[What's New Pussycat?]]''\n|  rowspan=\"3\" | Theme Singer\n| \n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[Promise Her Anything]]''\n| \n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]''\n|\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''The Special London Bridge Special''\n|   rowspan=\"2\" | \n|  a fantasy story about [[London Bridge]] being brought to America\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''On Happiness Island''\n| [[BBC]] special\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Pleasure Cove]]''\n| Raymond Gordon\n|  US TV Movie\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Fantasy Island]]''\n| Dick Turpin\n|  ([[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] series; season 7, episode 19)\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''The Ghosts of Oxford Street''\n|  Gordon Selfridge\n| Christmas TV Movie celebrating the 200th anniversary of London's Oxford Street\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[The Simpsons]]''\n|  rowspan=\"2\" | as Himself\n|  \"[[Marge Gets a Job]]\"\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Fresh Prince of Bel-Air]]''\n|  Season 3 Episode 18 : The {{sic|Alma Matter|hide=y|expected=Alma Mater}}\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''Silk n' Sabotage''\n|  Photographer\n|  \n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[The Jerky Boys: The Movie]]''\n|  rowspan=\"3\" | as Himself\n|  \n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Mars Attacks!]]''\n|  \n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Agnes Browne]]''\n|  \n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Emperor's New Groove]]''\n|   Theme Song Guy\n|  (animated film)\n|-\n| 2004\n|  ''[[Duck Dodgers (TV series)|Duck Dodgers]]''\n|   rowspan=\"2\" | as himself\n|  \"Talent Show A Go-Go\"<ref>[http://tomjonesonline.com/tom-jones-filmography.php]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090323050706/http://tomjonesonline.com/tom-jones-filmography.php |date=23 March 2009 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012\u201315, 2017\u2013\n| ''[[The Voice UK]]''\n|  Coach or \"judge\" and mentor for artists, Seasons 1 until 4 and 6 onwards\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Playhouse Presents]]''\n|   Ron\n|  Episode: \"King of the Teds\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Under Milk Wood]]''\n|   Captain Cat\n|  TV Film\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Superheroes Unite for BBC Children in Need]]''\n|   as Himself\n|  TV Film\n|}\n\n==Accolades==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=November 2017}}\n*1966: [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best New Artist]]\n*1966: Grammy Award ''nomination'' for Contemporary Rock & Roll Male Vocal Performance for \"What's New Pussycat?\"\n*1966: Grammy Award ''nomination'' for Contemporary Rock & Roll Single for \"It's Not Unusual\"\n*1970: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]] for ''This Is Tom Jones''\n*1970: [[Ivor Novello Award]] for International Artist of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theivors.com/archive/1970-1979/the-ivors-1970/|title=The Ivors 1970 \u2013 The Ivors|website=Theivors.com|accessdate=11 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307082550/http://theivors.com/archive/1970-1979/the-ivors-1970/|archive-date=7 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*1989: [[MTV Video Music Award \u2013 Breakthrough Video]] for \"Kiss\"\n*1989: Star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]\n*1999: appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE)<ref>{{cite news |title=New Years Honors List 1999 |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/55354/data.pdf |newspaper=The London Gazette}}</ref>\n*2000: [[2000 Brit Awards|Brit Award]] for Best British Male\n*2003: [[2003 Brit Awards|Brit Award]] for Outstanding Contribution to Music\n*2006: Knighthood for \"services to music\"\n*2017: [[Bambi Award]] in the category \"legend\"\n\n==See also==\n\n* {{books-inline|Tom Jones|Tom Jones}}\n* [[List of Welsh musicians]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bert Schwartz: ''Tom Jones'' ([[Grosset & Dunlap]], New York City, 1969) 76-103307\n* Peter Jones: ''Tom Jones: Biography of a Great Star'' ([[Avon Publishing]], 1970 (1st edition), 1971)\n* Colin MacFarlane: ''Tom Jones: The Boy from Nowhere'' ([[W. H. Allen]], London, 1988 St Martins Press, New York) {{ISBN|0-491-03118-1}}\n* Stafford Hildred & David Gritten: ''Tom Jones: A Biography'' (Isis Large Print Books, April 1991) {{ISBN|1-85089-486-8}}\n* Roger St. Pierre: ''Tom Jones: Quote Unquote'' (Parragon Book Service Ltd, Great Britain, 1996) {{ISBN|0-7525-1696-5}}\n* Stafford Hildred & David Gritten:  ''Tom Jones: A Biography'' (revised edition '98) ([[Sidgwick & Jackson]], 1998 an imprint of [[Macmillan Publishers]] Ltd) {{ISBN|0-283-06312-2}}\n* Chris Roberts:  ''Tom Jones'' (1st edition) ([[Virgin Books]], 1999 an imprint of Virgin Publishing Limited) {{ISBN|1-85227-846-3}}\n* Lucy Ellis, Bryony Sutherland: ''Tom Jones: Close Up'' ([[Omnibus Press]], 2000)  {{ISBN|0-7119-7549-3}} (HC) {{ISBN|0-7119-8645-2}} (Pb)\n* Robin Eggar: ''Tom Jones: The Biography'' (1st edition) (Headline Book Publishing, 2000) {{ISBN|0-7472-7578-5}}\n* ''Woodward v. Berkery'', 714 So.2d 1027 (Fla.App.4thDist. 1998)\n* Tom Jones: ''Over the Top and Back: The Autobiography'' ([[Michael Joseph (publisher)|Michael Joseph]], 8 October 2015) {{ISBN|0-7181-8068-2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.tomjones.com}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/57c6f649-6cde-48a7-8114-2a200247601a#p00b8ssm BBC Tom Jones Biography]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/music/sites/tom-jones/ BBC Wales Music]\n* [http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0311/07/lkl.00.html Transcript of interview with Larry King 7 November 2003]\n* {{IMDb name|429367|Tom Jones}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Shirley Bassey]]<br /><small>''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'', 1964</small>}} \n{{s-ttl|title=''[[James Bond]]'' title artist|years=<small>''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'', 1965</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nancy Sinatra]]<br /><small>''[[You Only Live Twice (film)|You Only Live Twice]]'', 1967}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Tom Jones}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best New Artist}}\n{{UK best-selling singles (by year) 1952\u20131969}}\n{{Welsh musicians}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Tom}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh singers]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:British Invasion artists]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Decca Records artists]]\n[[Category:Epic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Gut Records artists]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records artists]]\n[[Category:Island Records artists]]\n[[Category:Jive Records artists]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas shows]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lost Highway Records artists]]\n[[Category:Mercury Records artists]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Parrot Records artists]]\n[[Category:People from Pontypridd]]\n[[Category:Polydor Records artists]]\n[[Category:Singers awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Traditional pop music singers]]\n[[Category:V2 Records artists]]\n[[Category:Welsh autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Welsh baritones]]\n[[Category:Welsh crooners]]\n[[Category:Welsh expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Welsh male singers]]\n[[Category:Welsh people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Welsh pop singers]]\n[[Category:Welsh rock singers]]\n[[Category:ZTT Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Welsh singer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Tom Jones\n| honorific_prefix = Sir\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=UK|size=100|OBE}}\n| image            = Sir Tom Jones at The Queen's Birthday Party (cropped-2).jpg\n| caption          = Jones at [[The Queen's Birthday Party]] in 2018\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Thomas John Woodward<ref name=\"closeup\"/>\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1940|6|7}}\n| birth_place      = [[Treforest]], [[Pontypridd]], [[Glamorgan]], Wales\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*Pop\n*[[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]\n*[[soul music|soul]]\n*[[country music|country]]\n*[[gospel music|gospel]]\n}}\n| occupation       = Singer\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 1963\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n*[[Decca Records|Decca]]\n*[[Epic Records|Epic]]\n*[[Jive Records|Jive]]\n*[[Island Records|Island]]\n*[[Mercury Records|Mercury]]\n*[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]\n*[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n*[[V2 Records|V2]]\n*[[S-Curve Records|S-Curve]]\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|www.tomjones.com}}\n}}\n'''Sir Thomas John Woodward''' {{post-nominals|country=UK|size=100%|OBE}} (born 7 June 1940),<ref>[https://www.tomjones.com/bio  Biography, ''TomJones.com''] Retrieved 2 April 2020</ref> known professionally as '''Tom Jones''', is a [[Wales|Welsh]] singer. His career began with a string of top-ten hits in the mid-1960s. He has toured regularly, with appearances in Las Vegas (1967\u20132011). Jones's voice has been described by [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] as a \"full-throated, robust baritone\".<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/tom-jones-mn0000609396|title=Tom Jones|publisher=[[AllMusic]] |first= Stephen Thomas| last= Erlewine| accessdate= 3 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis performing range has included pop, [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]], [[show tune]]s, [[country music|country]], dance, [[soul music|soul]] and [[gospel music|gospel]].  In 2008, the ''New York Times'' called Jones a musical \"shape shifter\",<ref name=\"nyt01\"/> who could  \"slide from soulful rasp to pop croon, with a voice as husky as it was pretty\".<ref name= \"nyt01\">{{cite news | title = A Hip Shaker in His Prime, Among Hip Friends  | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | first = Greg | last= Evans | date = 13 April 2008  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/13/arts/television/13evan.html | accessdate=}}</ref> Jones has sold over 100&nbsp;million records, with 36 [[Top 40]] hits in the UK and 19 in the US, including  \"[[It's Not Unusual]]\", \"[[What's New Pussycat? (song)|What's New Pussycat]]\", the [[Thunderball (soundtrack)#Title theme change|theme song]] for the 1965 [[James Bond]] film ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'', \"[[Green, Green Grass of Home]]\", \"[[Delilah (Tom Jones song)|Delilah]]\", \"[[She's a Lady]]\", \"[[Kiss (Art of Noise song)|Kiss]]\" and \"[[Sex Bomb]]\".<ref>{{cite magazine| url= https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_wBeEDJhw110C |page= [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_wBeEDJhw110C/page/n27/mode/2up/search/tom+jones 28] |title= Celebrating Songs for 40 Years| work= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=20 June 2009 |accessdate=12 October 2015 |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |via= archive.org}}</ref>\n\nJones made his acting debut playing the lead role in the 1979 television film ''[[Pleasure Cove]]''. He played himself in [[Tim Burton]]'s 1996 film ''[[Mars Attacks!]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/7-things-you-definitely-never-8824732 |title=7 things you DEFINITELY never knew about Sir Tom Jones|first=Nathan|last=Bevan|date=12 March 2015 |website= Walesonline.com| accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref><ref name= czone>{{cite news| url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9218515/Tom-Jones-Acting-is-harder-than-I-thought.-I-was-out-of-my-comfort-zone.html|title=Tom Jones: 'Acting is harder than I thought. I was out of my comfort zone'| first= Charlotte| last= Williamson|date=22 April 2012| accessdate= 14 December 2017| website= The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> In 1970 he received a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]] nomination for hosting the television series ''[[This Is Tom Jones]]''. In 2012, he played a role in an episode of ''[[Playhouse Presents]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/showbiz/jim-cartwright-how-tom-jones-2033197 |title= Jim Cartwright on how Tom Jones went from Sex Bomb to depressed ex-Teddy Boy| first= Nathan| last=Bevan|date=27 April 2012| website= Walesonline.co.uk|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref> Jones received a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best New Artist]] in 1966, an [[MTV Video Music Award]] in 1989, as well as two [[Brit Awards]]: Best British Male in 2000 and the Outstanding Contribution to Music award in 2003. Jones was appointed Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in 1998 and [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the United Kingdom|knighted]] by Queen [[Elizabeth II]] for services to music in 2005. Jones experienced a resurgence in notability in the 2010s due to his coaching role on the television talent show ''[[The Voice UK]]'' from 2012 (with the exception of 2016).<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite magazine| url= http://www.list.co.uk/article/39019-the-voice-line-up-revealed/ |title=The Voice line-up revealed |magazine=The List |date=28 November 2011 |accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nJones was born Thomas John Woodward<ref name=\"closeup\">{{cite book| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=x43jHZliCN0C&pg=PT74&dq=%22thomas+john+woodward%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCWoVChMIroKNgYqEyQIVxHwPCh21YAvO#v=onepage&q=%22thomas%20john%20woodward%22&f=false |first1= Lucy| last1=  Ellis| first2= Bryony |last2= Sutherland| title= Tom Jones Close Up| publisher= Omnibus Press| year= 2009| isbn= 978-0711975491}}</ref> at 57 Kingsland Terrace, [[Treforest]], [[Pontypridd]], in [[Glamorgan]], [[South Wales]].<ref>''Entry of Birth'', sub-district of Pontypridd in the County of Glamorgan</ref><ref>{{cite book| first= Robin| last= Eggar| title= Tom Jones \u2013 The Biography| page= 14}}</ref> His parents were Thomas Woodward (31 March 1910 \u2013 5 October 1981), a coal miner, and Freda Jones (30 December 1914 \u2013 7 February 2003).<ref name=\"closeup\" /> Three of his grandparents were of English origin: his paternal grandfather, James Woodward, was an ironmonger's haulier from [[Gloucestershire]], and his paternal grandmother, Anne Woodward, was from [[Wiltshire]]. His maternal grandfather, Albert Jones, was Welsh, and his maternal grandmother, Ada Jones, was born in Pontypridd, to parents from [[Somerset]] and Wiltshire.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/5490511/Sir-Tom-Jones-is-English.html |title=Sir Tom Jones 'is English' |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=10 June 2009|location=London |issn=0307-1235 |oclc=49632006 |accessdate=4 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nJones attended Wood Road Infants School, Wood Road Junior School and Pontypridd Central [[Secondary Modern School]].<ref>{{cite book|date=8 October 2015| first= Tom| last= Jones|isbn=978-0-7181-8068-3|title=Over the Top and Back: The Autobiography|publisher=Michael Joseph|page=25}}</ref> He began singing at an early age: he would regularly sing at family gatherings, weddings and in his school choir. Jones did not like school or sports, but gained confidence through his singing talent.<ref name=\"DIDiscs TJ\">{{cite episode |title=Desert Island Discs with Tom Jones |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00tx499 |series=Desert Island Discs | serieslink=Desert Island Discs |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]] |airdate=26 September 2010}}</ref> At 12 he was diagnosed with [[tuberculosis]]. Many years later he said: \"I spent two years in bed recovering. It was the worst time of my life.\" During convalescence, he could do little else but listen to music and draw.<ref name= \"closeup\" />{{rp|9\u201310}}\n\nJones's bluesy singing style developed out of the sound of American [[soul music]]. His early influences included [[blues music|blues]], [[R&B]] and [[rock and roll]] singers [[Little Richard]], [[Solomon Burke]], [[Jackie Wilson]], [[Brook Benton]], [[Elvis Presley]] and [[Jerry Lee Lewis]].<ref name=\"rollingstone2015\">Appleford, Steve [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/tom-jones-on-meeting-elvis-recording-with-bacharach-panty-magnet-phase-20151215 \"Tom Jones on Meeting Elvis, Recording With Bacharach, 'Panty Magnet' Phase\"]. ''Rolling Stone''. 17 December 2015. Retrieved 17 December 2015.</ref>\n\nIn March 1957 Jones married his high school girlfriend, Linda Trenchard, when they were expecting a child together, both aged 16. The couple's son, Mark, was born in the month following their wedding. To support his young family, Jones took a job working in a glove factory and was later employed in construction.\n\n==Career==\n===Rise to fame===\nJones's voice has been described as a \"full-throated, robust [[baritone]]\".<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> He became the frontman in 1963 for Tommy Scott and the Senators, a Welsh [[beat group]]. They soon gained a local following and reputation in [[South Wales]]. In 1964, the group recorded several solo tracks with producer [[Joe Meek]], who took them to various record labels, but they had little success. Later that year, [[Decca Records|Decca]] producer Peter Sullivan saw Tommy Scott and the Senators performing in a club and directed them to manager [[Phil Solomon (music executive)|Phil Solomon]], but the partnership was short-lived.\n\nThe group continued to play gigs at dance halls and [[working men's club]]s in South Wales. One night at the Top Hat in [[Cwmtillery]], Jones was spotted by [[Gordon Mills]], a London-based manager who also originally hailed from [[South Wales]]. Mills became Jones's manager, took the young singer to London, and also renamed him \"Tom Jones\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/music/sites/tom-jones/pages/biography_02.shtml |title=Music \u2013 Tom Jones \u2013 Tom Jones biography \u2013 part two |website=BBC Wales |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> to exploit the popularity of the Academy Award-winning [[Tom Jones (1963 film)|1963 film]].<ref>{{cite magazine| work= [[Life (magazine)|Life]] |title= They can always go home to MAM| date= 18 September 1970 | page= [https://books.google.com/books?id=8lUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA54&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-ICLUK2LFKrMmAWW1IHQDw&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=&f=false 54]| volume= 69| number= 12 |quote= Mills promptly changed the singer's name to Tom Jones, to exploit the popularity of the current film by that name, and for six months he and Tom and the accompanists lived off a loan Mills talked a bank into giving them.}}</ref>\n\nEventually, Mills got Jones a recording contract with [[Decca Records|Decca]]. His first single, \"Chills and Fever\", was released in late 1964. It did not chart, but the follow-up, \"[[It's Not Unusual]]\", became an international [[chart-topper|hit]] after offshore [[pirate radio]] station [[Radio Caroline]] promoted it. The following year was the most prominent of Jones's career, making him one of the most popular vocalists of the [[British Invasion]]. In early 1965, \"It's Not Unusual\" reached No. 1 in the United Kingdom and the top ten in the United States. During 1965, Mills secured a number of film themes for Jones to record, including the theme songs for the film ''[[What's New Pussycat?]]'' (written by [[Burt Bacharach]] and [[Hal David]]) and also for the [[James Bond]] film ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]''.<ref name=\"BioPart3\"/> Jones was also awarded the [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist]] in 1966.<ref name=\"Grammy\">{{cite magazine| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=5SgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA13&dq=tom+jones+grammy+award+best+new+artist&hl=en&sa=X&ei=dYaBT4GRLqWi0QXsqK2LBw&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=tom%20jones%20grammy%20award%20best%20new%20artist&f=false |title= Naras Champions of 1965| page= 12| work= Billboard | date= 26 March 1966| access-date= 8 April 2012}}</ref> In Hollywood, Jones met [[Elvis Presley]] for the first time; he recalls Presley singing his song as he walked towards him on set.\n\nIn 1966, Jones's popularity began to slip somewhat, causing Mills to reshape the singer's image into that of a [[crooner]]. Jones also began to sing material that appealed to a wider audience, such as the country hit \"[[Green, Green Grass of Home]]\". The strategy worked, and Jones returned to the top of the charts in the UK and began hitting the Top 40 again in the US. For the remainder of the decade, he scored a string of hits on both sides of the Atlantic, including \"[[I'll Never Fall in Love Again (Lonnie Donegan song)|I'll Never Fall in Love Again]]\", \"I'm Coming Home\", and \"Delilah\", each of which reached No. 2 in the UK chart.<ref name=\"Tom Jones Nostalgia Central\">{{cite web| url= http://www.nostalgiacentral.com/music/tomjones.htm | title= Tom Jones| website= nostalgiacentral.com |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060721100011/http://www.nostalgiacentral.com/music/tomjones.htm |archivedate= 21 July 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.classicbands.com/tomjones.html |title=Tom Jones |website=Classicbands.com |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Las Vegas===\nIn 1967, Jones performed in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] for the first time, at the [[Flamingo Las Vegas|Flamingo]].<ref name=\"BioPart3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/music/sites/tom-jones/pages/biography_03.shtml |title=Music \u2013 Tom Jones \u2013 Tom Jones biography \u2013 part three |website=BBC Wales |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> His performances and style of dress became part of his stage act, and increasingly featured his open, half-unbuttoned shirts and tight trousers. He soon chose to record less, instead concentrating on his lucrative club performances.\n\nJones and his idol [[Elvis Presley]] met in 1965 at the [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] film stage, when Elvis was filming ''[[Paradise, Hawaiian Style]]''.<ref name=\"rollingstone2015\"/><ref name=\"BioPart3\"/> They became good friends, spending more and more time together in Las Vegas and duetting until the early hours at Presley's private suite. The friendship endured until Presley's death in 1977.<ref name=\"BioPart3\"/> Jones's guitarist between 1969 and 1974 was [[Big Jim Sullivan]], who also met and formed a friendship with Presley.\n\nJones played in Las Vegas at least one week each year until 2011.\n\n===Television===\n[[File:Janis Joplin Tom Jones 1969.JPG|thumb|left|Jones duetting with [[Janis Joplin]] on the television programme ''[[This Is Tom Jones]]'' in 1969]]\nJones had an internationally successful television variety show titled ''[[This Is Tom Jones]]'' from 1969 to 1971.  The [[Associated Television]]-produced show was worth a reported {{US$|9000000|1971|about=yes|round=-5}} to Jones over three years.  It was broadcast by [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] in the UK and by the [[American Broadcasting Company]] in the US.  As a result of the show, Jones was nominated in 1970 for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|a \"best actor\" Golden Globe]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/music/sites/tom-jones/pages/this-is-tom-jones-dvd.shtml |publisher= BBC| place= Wales| title= ''This Is Tom Jones'' DVD review| date= | access-date= 5 January 2013}}</ref> From 1980 to 1981, he had a second television variety show, ''[[Tom Jones (TV series)|Tom Jones]]'', which was produced in [[Vancouver]], Canada, and lasted 24 episodes.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Both television shows were the subject of litigation with the original licence holder [[C/F International]].  {{As of|2004|12}}, C/F International was a secured judgment creditor of [[Classic World Productions]] and its principal, Darryl Payne, for approximately {{US$|1000000|2004|about=yes|round=-5}}, and was the principal secured creditor at the time of the subsequent bankruptcy filing by the company.  C/F International's action against Classic World Productions and owner Darryl Payne was based on unpaid [[royalty payment]]s from ''This Is Tom Jones''<ref>{{cite web|last=Hise |first=Micheal |url=http://www.tv.com/this-is-tom-jones/show/1146/summary.html |title=This is Tom Jones |website=TV.com |date=12 February 2008 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> and related recordings.<ref>[http://www.websupp.org/data/DNJ/2:01-cv-03624-94-DNJ.pdf C/F International Inc. v. Classic World Productions et al.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327115100/http://www.websupp.org/data/DNJ/2%3A01-cv-03624-94-DNJ.pdf |date=27 March 2009 }}, New Jersey District Court, Judgement of 16 February 2006 at page 2; Websupp.org.</ref> ''This Is Tom Jones'' is sold on DVD by [[Time Life]] rather than by Classic World Productions or C/F International.<ref>{{Cite web | url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110727053615/http://www.timelife.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/ProductDisplay?catalogId=10001&storeId=1001&langId=&top_category=90003&productId=211811 |title = Generic Error}}</ref>\n\nC/F International's rights to later Tom Jones material were also disputed.  In March 2007, Tom Jones and Tom Jones Enterprises sued C/F International to stop the company from licensing sound recordings made from the 1981 ''Tom Jones'' series.  It was contended that any rights that C/F International had to licence the ''Tom Jones'' show did not include the right to make and licence separate recordings of the performances on the show, and that any rights that C/F International had in the ''Tom Jones'' show no longer existed because of numerous breaches of contract.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storyCode=26492&sectioncode=1 |title=Tom Jones seeks injunction over recordings |magazine=Music Week |date=2 March 2007 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> Examples of contentious CDs are ''Live on the Tom Jones Show'', released in 2006, and ''Greatest Hits Live'', originally issued by C/F International in 1981 and later licensed to and issued by Prism Leisure Corporation as ''30 Greatest Hits \u2013 Live in Concert''.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.7digital.com/artists/various-artists/live-on-the-tom-jones-show/ |title= Live on The Tom Jones Show| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080124062521/http://www.7digital.com/artists/various-artists/live-on-the-tom-jones-show/ |archivedate=24 January 2008 | website= 7digital.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.discogs.com/Tom-Jones-30-Greatest-Hits-Live-In-Concert/release/10485850| website= Discogs.com| title= 30 Greatest Hits \u2013 Live in Concert| access-date= March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000URRAYC |title=Tom Jones \u2013 30 Greatest Hits/Live in Concert | website= Amazon.com |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 April 1970, [[CBS]] released the television special ''[[Raquel! (TV program)|Raquel!]]'' directed by [[David Winters (choreographer)|David Winters]], in which he was a guest. It starred [[Raquel Welch]], and other guests included [[Bob Hope]] and [[John Wayne]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0174154/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Raquel! (1970 TV Movie): Full Cast & Crew|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> It was filmed in London, Paris, [[Acapulco]], Mexico City, [[Yucatan]], [[Big Sur]], and Los Angeles and featured lavish production numbers. Welch and Jones combined musical and comedic talents on classic rock 'n' roll standards of the era.<ref name=\"HBJ\">{{cite book|title=Television: The Business Behind the Box.|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/televisionbusine00brow|chapter-url-access=registration|last=Brown|first=Les|publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich|year=1971|isbn=978-0-15-688440-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/televisionbusine00brow/page/187 187], 188|chapter= Raquel! }}</ref> Produced by Winters' company Winters/Rosen for CBS-TV, originally co-sponsored by [[Coca-Cola]] and [[Motorola]]. On the day of the premiere, the show received a 51% share on the National ARB Ratings and an impressive Overnight New York Nielsen Rating of 58% share.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://davidwinters.net/pic3.htm|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806025805/http://www.davidwinters.net/pic3.htm|archivedate=6 August 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=19 May 2011|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nightflight.com/happy-birthday-today-to-raquel-welch-her-1970-primetime-tv-special-will-melt-your-mind/|title=Happy Birthday today to Raquel Welch: Her 1970 primetime TV special will melt your mind!|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411013143/http://nightflight.com/happy-birthday-today-to-raquel-welch-her-1970-primetime-tv-special-will-melt-your-mind/|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=|access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Decline and resurgence===\n[[File:Celebrity Star Tom Jones Orpheum Theater Memphis TN.jpg|thumb|The star commemorating Jones at the [[Orpheum Theatre (Memphis, Tennessee)|Orpheum Theatre, Memphis]]]]\nIn the 1970s, Jones toured with the female singing groups [[Quiet Elegance]] and [[the Blossoms]] as his backing groups. He had a number of hit singles, including \"[[She's a Lady]]\", \"[[Till (song)|Till]]\", and \"[[The Young New Mexican Puppeteer]]\", but in the mid-1970s his popularity declined. He did, however, have a big hit in 1976 with \"[[Say You'll Stay Until Tomorrow]]\", which went to No. 1 on the US country chart, No. 15 on the Billboard Hot 100 and reached No. 40 on the UK Singles Chart.\n\nIn 1972, he reunited with director and choreographer [[David Winters (choreographer)|David Winters]] for the musical television special [[The Special London Bridge Special|''The Special London Bridge Special'']], co-starring [[Jennifer O'Neill]]. Others who participated as guests included [[The Carpenters]], [[Kirk Douglas]], [[Jonathan Winters]], [[Hermione Gingold]], [[Lorne Greene]], [[Chief Dan George]], [[Charlton Heston]], [[George Kirby]], [[Michael Landon]], [[Terry-Thomas]], [[Engelbert Humperdinck (singer)|Engelbert Humperdinck]], [[Elliott Gould]], [[Merle Park]], and [[Rudolf Nureyev]].<ref name=\"closeup\" /><ref>{{Cite news|date=7 May 1972|title=Introducing London Bridge Special| journal= [[The Anniston Star]] |volume= 93 |pages= 48|via= Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Indian chief in Disney tribe|journal= [[The Herald-News]] |volume=103|pages=39|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976, Jones was set to make his film debut in the film ''Yockowald'', in which he was to play a [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] assassin. The film was shelved after the production ran out of money three weeks into filming.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/7-things-you-definitely-never-8824732|title=7 things you DEFINITELY never knew about Sir Tom Jones |first= Nathan |last= Bevan |date=12 March 2015 |website= Walesonline.co.uk|accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979, Jones made his acting debut in ''[[Pleasure Cove]]'', an [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television film which was an unsuccessful pilot for a potential television series along the lines of ''[[Love Boat]]'' and ''[[Fantasy Island]]''. In the film, he played a suave conman named Raymond Gordon staying at the holiday island resort of the title. His co-stars in the film included [[Constance Forslund]], [[Tanya Roberts]] and [[David Hasselhoff]].<ref name= \"closeup\" />{{rp|326}} He guest-starred in an episode of ''[[Fantasy Island]]'' in 1984.\n\nIn the early 1980s, Jones started to record country music. From 1980 to 1986, he had nine songs in the US country top 40, yet failed to crack the top 100 in the UK or the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"Tom Jones Discography\">{{cite web| url= http://www.tomjonesonline.com/tom-jones-discography.php| title= Discography| website= tomjonesonline.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100221021950/http://www.tomjonesonline.com/tom-jones-discography.php |archivedate=21 February 2010 | access-date= }}</ref> Jones's manager Gordon Mills died of cancer on 29 July 1986, and Jones's son Mark became his manager.<ref name= \"closeup\" />{{rp|271, 275}}\n\nIn 1987, Tom Jones re-entered the singles chart with \"[[Matador (English musical)|A Boy From Nowhere]]\", which went to No. 2 in the UK. The following year, he covered [[Prince (musician)|Prince]]'s \"[[Kiss (Tom Jones song)|Kiss]]\" with [[Art of Noise]]. The song reached No. 5 in the UK and No. 31 in the US. The video for \"Kiss\" was played frequently on MTV and [[VH1]], and won the [[MTV Video Music Award \u2013 Breakthrough Video|MTV Video Music Award for Breakthrough Video]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1989/mtvvmas.htm |title=1989 MTV Video Music Awards |publisher=Rock on the Net |date=6 September 1989 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nJones received a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in 1989, located at 6608 [[Hollywood Boulevard]], Los Angeles, California, in front of [[Frederick's of Hollywood]]. In 1992, he made his first appearance at the UK's [[Glastonbury Festival]], and in 1993 he appeared as himself in episodes of two popular US sitcoms, ''[[The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air]]'' and ''[[The Simpsons]]''.\n\nJones signed with [[Interscope Records]] in 1993 and released the album ''The Lead And How To Swing It''. The first single, \"If I Only Knew\", went to No. 11 in the UK.<ref name=\"Tom Jones Discography\"/> Jones performed the song at the [[1994 MTV Europe Music Awards]], for which he also served as host. In 1997, Jones contributed to the soundtrack for the UK comedy film ''[[The Full Monty]]'', recording \"[[You Can Leave Your Hat On]]\".<ref>{{cite web| first= Robert |last= Carlyle |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-full-monty-original-soundtrack-r307874 |title=The Full Monty [Original Soundtrack&#93; \u2013 Original Soundtrack &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date=12 August 1997 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, he appeared as himself in [[Tim Burton]]'s ensemble science-fiction comedy film ''[[Mars Attacks!]]''. A scene in the film features Jones performing on stage when aliens attack and he manages to escape with a gun.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/20-knew-ol'-tom-jones-60-singer-surprise-star-mars-attacks-article-1.741534|title=20 Things you Never Knew About Ol Tom Jones is Surprise Star of Mars Attacks |website=Daily News|location=New York|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Jones released the album ''[[Reload (Tom Jones album)|Reload]]'', a collection of cover duets with artists such as [[the Cardigans]], [[Natalie Imbruglia]], [[Cerys Matthews]], [[Van Morrison]], [[Mousse T]], [[Portishead (band)|Portishead]], [[Stereophonics]] and [[Robbie Williams]]. The album went to No. 1 in the UK and sold over 4 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wBeEDJhw110C&pg=PA28&lpg=PA28&dq=tom+jones+reload+4+million+worldwide#v=onepage&q=tom%20jones%20reload%204%20million%20worldwide&f=false|title=Howie Richmond Hitmaker Award: Tom Jones|magazine=Billboard|page=28|date=20 June 2009|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref> Five singles from ''Reload'' charted in the UK top 40.<ref name=\"Tom Jones Discography\"/><ref name=\"Tom Jones Bio\">{{cite web| website= yuddy.com| url= http://www.yuddy.com/celebrity/tom-jones/bio| title= Tom Jones Biography |date= | access-date= |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100112223520/http://www.yuddy.com/celebrity/tom-jones/bio |archivedate=12 January 2010 }}</ref> The single \"[[Sex Bomb (song)|Sex Bomb]]\" was released in early 2000 and became the album's biggest single, reaching No. 3 in the UK Singles Chart.\n\n===Into the 21st century===\nUS President [[Bill Clinton]] invited Jones to perform on New Year's Eve at the 2000 millennium celebrations in Washington DC. In 2000, Jones garnered a number of honours for his work, including a [[BRIT Awards|BRIT Award]] for Best British Male.<ref name=\"Brits\">[http://www.brits.co.uk/artist/tom-jone ]{{Dead link|date=October 2015}}</ref> He was also hired as the new voice of Australia's [[National Rugby League]], singing in an advertisement to market the 2000 season.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mealey |first=Rachel| website= abc.net.au |title=Tom Jones the new voice of NRL |location=Australia  |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=29 January 2000 |url= http://www.abc.net.au/am/stories/s96345.htm |accessdate=3 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Jones released the album ''[[Mr. Jones (Tom Jones album)|Mr. Jones]]'', which was produced by Haitian-American rapper [[Wyclef Jean]]. The album and the first single, \"Tom Jones International\", were top 40 hits in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B00006J9NE |title=Mr Jones: Amazon.co.uk: Music |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nJones received the Brit Award for Outstanding Contribution to Music in 2003.<ref name=\"Brits\"/> The following year, he teamed up with pianist [[Jools Holland]] and released ''Tom Jones & Jools Holland'', a roots rock 'n' roll album. It peaked at No. 5 in the UK.<ref name=\"Tom Jones Discography\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B0002Y9TRO |title=Tom Jones & Jools Holland| website= Amazon.com |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 May 2005, in celebration of his upcoming 65th birthday, Jones returned to his homeland to perform a concert in [[Ynysangharad Park]], Pontypridd before an audience of about 20,000. This was his first performance in Pontypridd since 1964.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/south_east/4590941.stm |title=Home town triumph for Tom Jones |date=29 May 2005 |publisher=BBC News   |accessdate=23 November 2011}}</ref> That same year, the BBC reported that Jones was Wales's wealthiest entertainer, having amassed a [[Wealth|fortune]] of \u00a3175,000,000.<ref>{{cite news |date=2 April 2005 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/4401733.stm |title=Financier heads Welsh rich list |publisher=BBC News  |accessdate=12 February 2008}}</ref> Jones collaborated with Australian pop singer [[John Farnham]] in 2005 and released the live album ''[[John Farnham & Tom Jones \u2013 Together in Concert]]''. The following year, Jones worked with [[Chicane (recording artist)|Chicane]] and released the dance track \"[[Stoned in Love]]\", which went to No. 7 in the UK Singles Chart.<ref name=\"Tom Jones Discography\"/>\n\nJones, who had been awarded an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in 1999, was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] by Queen [[Elizabeth II]] in 2006 at [[Buckingham Palace]] for his services to music.<ref name=\"BBC2006\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/4853732.stm| title=Tom Jones collects his knighthood|publisher=BBC News | date=29 March 2006| accessdate=29 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/tom-jones |title=Tom Jones  |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 June 2012 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> After receiving a knighthood, Jones stated: \"When you first come into show business and get a hit record, it is the start of something. As time goes by it just gets better. This is the best thing I have had. It's a wonderful feeling, a heady feeling.\"<ref name=\"BBC2006\"/>\n\n===2007\u20132009===\nOn 1 July 2007, Jones was among the artists who performed at [[Wembley Stadium]] at the [[Concert for Diana]], joined on stage by guitarist [[Joe Perry (musician)|Joe Perry]] of [[Aerosmith]] and soul singer [[Joss Stone]]. In addition to performing some of his own songs, the group covered the [[Arctic Monkeys]] song, \"[[I Bet You Look Good on the Dancefloor]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.covermesongs.com/2010/08/tom-jones-w-joe-perry-i-bet-you-look-good-on-the-dancefloor.html |title=Song of the Day: Tom Jones w/ Joe Perry, \"I Bet You Look Good on the Dancefloor\" (Arctic Monkeys cover) \u00bb Cover Me |website=Covermesongs.com |date=27 August 2010 |accessdate=14 July 2011}}</ref> A boxing fan, Jones has performed national anthems before a number of boxing matches. He sang \"[[God Save the Queen]]\", the national anthem of the United Kingdom, before the [[Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Ricky Hatton|Floyd Mayweather-Ricky Hatton fight]] in 2007; he sang \"[[Hen Wlad Fy Nhadau]]\", the Welsh national anthem, at the [[Bernard Hopkins vs. Joe Calzaghe|Bernard Hopkins-Joe Calzaghe fight]] between fellow Welshman [[Joe Calzaghe]] and [[Bernard Hopkins]] in 2008; and he sang \"God Save the Queen\" before the [[Manny Pacquiao vs. Ricky Hatton|Manny Pacquiao-Ricky Hatton fight]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/more_sport/article3736265.ece|title=The Times & The Sunday Times|website=The Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/more_sport/article3023565.ece |title=The Times |work=The Times |date=28 September 2015 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.eastsideboxing.com/news.php?p=19671&more=1]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601161715/http://www.eastsideboxing.com/news.php?p=19671&more=1 |date=1 June 2009 }}</ref>\n[[File:Tom Jones Hampton Court Palace 2007.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Performing at [[Hampton Court Palace]] in London, 2007]]\n\nIn 2008, he released ''24 Hours'' on [[S-Curve Records]], his first album of new material to be issued in the United States for over 15 years. Jones, who was still performing over 200 dates a year as he approached his seventieth birthday, set out on a world tour to promote the album. \"The fire is still in me. Not to be an oldie, but a goodie. I want to be a contender\", Jones said.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7620450.stm |title=Sir Tom Jones eyes fresh comeback |publisher=BBC News  |date=17 September 2008 |accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Russell |first=Gwen |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B001G5SDA2 |title=24 Hours: Tom Jones: Music |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=14 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tomjones.com/news/santiago-takes-its-hat-off-to-tom-jones-santiago-times-review/ |title=Santiago takes its hat off to Tom Jones \u2013 Santiago Times Review |publisher=Tom Jones |accessdate=12 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016072640/http://www.tomjones.com/news/santiago-takes-its-hat-off-to-tom-jones-santiago-times-review/ |archive-date=16 October 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Also in 2008, Jones was inducted into the Hit Parade Hall of Fame. On 16 November 2008, he was invited to perform on BBC's ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''; he performed the debut single from ''24 Hours'', \"If He Should Ever Leave You\", which was named the ninth-best song of 2008 by [[Spinner (web site)|Spinner]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spinner.com/2008/12/12/best-songs-of-2008-no-9 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306003200/http://www.spinner.com/2008/12/12/best-songs-of-2008-no-9 |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 March 2012 |title=Best Songs of 2008: No. 9 |work=Spinner |accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/8299511.stm |title=In conversation with Sir Tom  |publisher=BBC News  |date=9 October 2009 |accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|I39LiZjqDes|\"Tom Jones 'If He Should Ever Leave You' Strictly Come Dancing\"}}</ref> One of the songs from ''24 Hours'', \"Give a Little Love\", would later be featured in the first trailer for the 2010 comedy film, ''[[Little Fockers]]''.\n\nIn February 2009, Jones appeared in an exclusive [[Take-Away Show]] with [[Vincent Moon]], performing three songs live in front of a camera in a New York hotel room.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blogotheque.net/Tom-Jones |title=Tom Jones&nbsp;\u2013 LA BLOGOTHEQUE |website=Blogotheque.net |accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref> In March 2009, Jones went to the top of the UK Music Charts for the third time in his career with a cover of \"[[Islands in the Stream (song)|Islands in the Stream]]\", sung with [[Ruth Jones (actress)|Ruth Jones]], [[Rob Brydon]] and [[Robin Gibb]], who co-wrote the original with his brothers [[Barry Gibb|Barry]] and [[Maurice Gibb|Maurice]]. The record, which was inspired by the song's having featured in the BBC's hit sitcom ''[[Gavin & Stacey]]'', was released in aid of [[Comic Relief]] and reached No. 1 in March 2009.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/269201/u2-comic-relief-top-uk-charts |title=U2, Comic Relief Top U.K. Charts |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2010\u2013present===\n[[File:Tom Jones concert.jpg|thumb|200px|Jones at [[House of Blues]], [[Anaheim, California|Anaheim]], 2009]]\nJones's album ''[[Praise & Blame]]'' was released on 26 July 2010. The album, consisting primarily of gospel and blues songs, included covers of songs by [[Bob Dylan]], [[John Lee Hooker]] and [[Billy Joe Shaver]], and featured guest musicians such as [[Booker T. Jones|Booker T.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/tom-jones/51098 |title=Tom Jones covering Bob Dylan, John Lee Hooker on new album |work=NME |date=17 May 2010 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Kitty |last=Empire |title=Tom Jones: Praise & Blame |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jul/25/tom-jones-praise-blame-review |date=24 July 2010 |accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 June 2010, which was Jones's seventieth birthday, the single \"Burning Hell\", a cover of the John Lee Hooker song from the ''Praise & Blame'' album, was released. In July 2010, it was reported that David Sharpe, vice-president of [[Island Records]] (to whom Jones had moved, from [[EMI]], for \u00a31.5m in October 2009), had emailed colleagues demanding that they \"pull back this project immediately or get my money back\" and asking if the spiritually themed record had been a \"sick joke\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/7870995/Tom-Joness-record-boss-complains-his-new-album-sounds-like-hymns.html |title=Tom Jones's record boss complains his new album sounds like hymns |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> Jones later strongly criticised Sharpe and said that he was furious about the leaked email.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2010/07/10/tom-jones-furious-at-record-company-boss-s-comments-91466-26823038/ |title=Tom Jones furious at record company boss's comments |work=Wales Online |date= 9 July 2010|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Jones appeared on the penultimate episode of ''[[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]'' and performed \"Burning Hell\". In August 2010, ''Praise & Blame'' debuted at No. 2 on the UK album chart.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/latest/2010/08/01/eminem-beats-tom-jones-to-no-1-spot-115875-22457228/ | title = Eminem beats Tom Jones to No 1 spot | date = 1 August 2010 | newspaper = Mirror | location = London | accessdate =24 August 2010}}</ref> By 2010 Jones had sold a total of over 100 million records.<ref name=\"3News_142546\">{{cite news |url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Tom-Jones-Its-not-unusual-no/tabid/728/articleID/142546/Default.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929131157/http://www.3news.co.nz/Tom-Jones-Its-not-unusual-no/tabid/728/articleID/142546/Default.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 September 2012 |title=Tom Jones: 'It's not unusual, no' |date=18 February 2010 |work=[[3 News]] |accessdate=23 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 September 2010, Jones performed for an audience of 50,000 at the ''[[Help for Heroes]]'' charity concert at [[Twickenham Stadium]] performing \"[[Sister Rosetta Tharpe|Strange Things Are Happening Every Day]]\" and his hit \"[[Green, Green Grass of Home]]\". On 22 September, Jones appeared on the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' at the [[Ed Sullivan Theater]] in New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvmaze.com/episodes/27347/the-late-show-with-david-letterman-2010-09-22-joaquin-phoenix-tom-jones|title=Joaquin Phoenix, Tom Jones \u2013 The Late Show with David Letterman 2010-09-22|publisher=TVmaze|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, Jones appeared as a guest vocalist on the debut album ''[[Let Them Talk (Hugh Laurie album)|Let Them Talk]]'' by [[Hugh Laurie]]. On 15 May 2011, he appeared alongside Laurie in the UK [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] series ''Perspectives'', singing music from the album in [[New Orleans]].<ref>[http://www.itv.com/perspectives/essays/hugh-laurie/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://archive.today/20130103095138/http://www.itv.com/perspectives/essays/hugh-laurie/ |date=3 January 2013 }}</ref> On 25 May 2011, he appeared on '' [[American Idol (season 10)|American Idol]] '' after a medley of his hits performed by the American Idol \"Top 13\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Herndon |first=Jessica |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20497722,00.html |title=Tom Jones, Tony Bennett, Tim McGraw Perform at Idol Finale |work=People  |date=26 May 2011 |accessdate=14 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nJones released a single on 19 March 2012, produced by former [[White Stripes]] frontman [[Jack White (musician)|Jack White]], called ''Evil''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/jack-white/61946 |title=Hear Jack White's 'Evil' collaboration with Tom Jones |website=NME |date=9 February 2012 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The single was first made available through independent record shops in 7\" vinyl format on 5 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecmuwebsite.com/article/tom-jones-and-jack-white-single-to-be-sold-nationwide/ |title=Tom Jones and Jack White single to be sold nationwide |work=Thecmuwebsite.com |date=27 February 2012 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> An exclusive [[Unusual types of gramophone records|three-coloured vinyl]] was also sold at only one shop \u2013 [[Spillers Records]] in [[Cardiff]]. The shop, from which Jones bought records as a schoolboy in the 1950s and early 1960s, was founded in 1894 and is listed in ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' as the oldest record shop in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/9100881/Tom-Jones-single-to-be-sold-in-one-shop-only.html|title=Tom Jones single to be sold in one shop only|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=23 February 2012|accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, Jones became a coach on the BBC talent show ''[[The Voice UK]]''.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> Jones was joined by [[will.i.am]], [[Jessie J]] and [[Danny O'Donoghue]]. He mentored [[Leanne Mitchell]] to win the first series. Jones returned to coach in 2013, 2014 and 2015. In August 2015, it was announced that Jones's contract with the show would not be renewed and that he would be replaced by [[Boy George]]. Jones criticised BBC executives for \"sub-standard behaviour\", having not consulted with him and informing him only 24 hours before the official announcement.<ref>{{cite news|author=Rose Troup Buchanan |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/tom-jones-dropped-from-the-voice-singer-criticises-bbc-executives-for-substandard-behaviour-after-hes-axed-from-fifth-series-10456948.html |title=Tom Jones dropped from The Voice: Singer criticises 'BBC executives' for 'sub-standard behaviour' after he's axed from fifth series |work=[[The Independent]] |date=15 August 2015 |accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, Jones released the album ''Spirit in the Room'' on [[Island Records]]/[[Universal Music]]. The track listing included covers of songs by [[Paul McCartney]], [[Paul Simon]], [[Leonard Cohen]] and [[Richard and Linda Thompson]], [[Blind Willie Johnson]], [[Tom Waits]] and [[the Low Anthem]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/may/20/tom-jones-spirit-room-review?newsfeed=true |title=Tom Jones: Spirit in the Room |work=The Guardian |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, he starred in a one-off television drama titled \"King of the Teds\" which aired on [[Sky Arts]] as part of a series of standalone teleplays for ''[[Playhouse Presents]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9244325/King-of-the-Teds-Sky-Arts-review.html|title=King of the Teds, Sky Arts, review|first=Rachel|last=Ward|date=4 May 2012|accessdate=14 December 2017|website=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 June 2012, Jones performed at the Queen's [[Diamond Jubilee Concert]] in front of [[Buckingham Palace]], singing \"Delilah\" and \"[[Mama Told Me Not to Come]]\".{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn 18 August 2012, Jones performed a fifty-minute set at the [[V Festival]]\u2019s Weston Park site in [[Staffordshire]].<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/v-festival-liveblog-gossip-pictures-1264340 \"Liveblog: Relive our V Festival weekend, all of the gossip, pictures and video from the star-studded VIP area\"]. ''Daily Mirror''. Retrieved 22 August 2012.</ref> On 9 September 2012, Jones headlined at [[BBC Radio 2]]'s Live in Hyde Park festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/e68v4f/acts/ajdg9r |title=Radio 2 Live in Hyde Park \u2013 2012 \u2013 Acts \u2013 Sir Tom Jones |publisher=BBC |date=9 September 1015 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, Jones opened for [[Morrissey]] at a special show in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Tom Jones and Sir Cliff Richard to support Morrissey at major US shows|url=https://www.nme.com/news/morrissey/75468|accessdate=15 February 2014|newspaper=[[NME]]|date=13 February 2014}}</ref> On 27 September 2014, Jones performed at the [[Australian Football League]]'s pre-game entertainment for the [[2014 AFL Grand Final|2014 Grand Final]] along with [[Ed Sheeran]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2014-09-01/tom-jones-to-star-on-gf-stage |title=What's news, pussycat? Tom Jones, Ed Sheeran to star on GF stage |website=AFL.com.au |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Jones announced the long-awaited release of his album ''[[Long Lost Suitcase]]'', on 9 October, through Virgin/EMI. The album is the third in a trilogy of albums, following ''Praise & Blame'' (2010) and ''Spirit in the Room'' (2012). The album's track titles are interwoven into the chapters of his autobiography ''Over the Top and Back'' released at the same time. It was produced by [[Ethan Johns]] and the diverse range of compositions includes songs from [[Gillian Welch]], [[the Rolling Stones]], [[Hank Williams]] and [[the Milk Carton Kids]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.music-news.com/news/UK/91959/Read |title=Tom Jones announces new album |publisher=Music-News.com |date=2 September 2015 |accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, Jones appeared alongside [[Rob Brydon]] in a special 90-minute show, from the [[Wembley Arena|SSE Arena, Wembley]], for BBC's [[Children in Need]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06pf7sb|title=Tom Jones & Rob Brydon: One Big Night for Children in Need|work=BBC One|date=12 November 2015|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he appeared on the BBC's ''[[Jools' Annual Hootenanny]]'', broadcast on New Year's Eve, on which he duetted with [[Paul Weller]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01pk3kf|title=Jools' Annual Hootenanny, 2015/16|work=[[BBC Two]]|date=31 December 2015|accessdate=2 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he returned to ''The Voice'' as a coach for [[The Voice UK (series 6)|series 6]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-01-09/who-is-tom-jones-the-voice-uk-coach-profile|title=Who is The Voice UK 2017 judge Tom Jones?|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=9 January 2017|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he embarked on a live summer tour, which was planned to run from 1 May to 11 August.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bestclassicbands.com/tom-jones-2018-tour-dates-4-23-18/|title=Tom Jones Adds 2018 Tour Dates \u2013 Best Classic Bands|date=11 June 2015|work=Best Classic Bands|access-date=31 July 2018}}</ref> In July, however, many shows were cancelled due to sickness or bad weather.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/news/sir-tom-jones-78-makes-triumphant-return-to-the-stage-after-bacterial-infection-and-thunderstorms-forced-him-to-miss-six-shows/ar-BBLhslV|title=Sir Tom Jones, 78, makes triumphant return to the stage... after bacterial infection and thunderstorms forced him to miss SIX shows|publisher=MSN|access-date=31 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731123522/https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/news/sir-tom-jones-78-makes-triumphant-return-to-the-stage-after-bacterial-infection-and-thunderstorms-forced-him-to-miss-six-shows/ar-BBLhslV|archive-date=31 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-44885944|title=Tom Jones postpones show due to illness|date=19 July 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 June 2019 ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Jones among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=28 June 2019 |date=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJones was married to Linda (born 1941 as Melinda Rose Trenchard) from 2 March 1957 until her death on 10 April 2016.<ref>{{cite book|date=8 October 2015|author=Tom Jones|isbn=978-0-7181-8068-3|title=Over the Top and Back: The Autobiography|publisher=Michael Joseph|pages=63\u201364}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/tom-jones-wife-linda-dies-11167791#rlabs=1%20p$7|title=Tom Jones' wife Linda dies after \"short but fierce\" battle with cancer|author=Mears, Tyler|date=11 April 2016|work=Wales Online|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> They stayed married despite his many well-publicised [[infidelity|infidelities]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/tom-jones-i-still-love-2125116|title=Tom Jones 'I still love Linda'|work=[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]|date=21 February 2009|accessdate=2 January 2016}}</ref> The couple had one son, Mark Woodward (born 1957).\n\nJones has stated that he had sex with up to 250 groupies a year at the height of his fame.<ref name= czone /> His [[philandering]] once led Linda to assault him. Jones had [[affair]]s with well-known women, including [[Mary Wilson (singer)|Mary Wilson]] of [[the Supremes]], TV host [[Charlotte Laws]]<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.sabado.pt/vida/detalhe/charlotte_fura_festas_e_vingadora.html|title=Charlotte Laws: fura-festas e vingadora |website= Sabado.pt |accessdate= 12 October 2015}}</ref> and former Miss World [[Marjorie Wallace]].<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/the-voice-judge-tom-jones-affair-777978 |title= Tom Jones, the Miss World who stole his heart and the faithful wife who wrested it back| first= Dominic |last= Herbert| work= Daily Mirror| date= 1 April 2012| access-date= 12 April 2012}}</ref> In a 2008 interview with ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' magazine, [[Cassandra Peterson]] (better known as ''Elvira, Mistress of the Dark'') revealed she lost her [[virginity]] to Jones.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2008/07/09/elvira_was_deflowered_by_tom_jones_neede |title=Elvira Was Deflowered By Tom Jones; Needed Stitches |date=9 July 2008 |accessdate=3 October 2011 |magazine=StarPulse.com |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080712184407/http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2008/07/09/elvira_was_deflowered_by_tom_jones_neede |archivedate= 12 July 2008 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nOne affair resulted in the birth of a son. In October 1987, while on tour in the US, Jones had a brief relationship with model Katherine Berkery, who then discovered she was pregnant. After a legal battle that included [[DNA]] [[paternity test|testing]], a United States court ruled in 1989 that Jones was the boy's father. Jones denied the court's findings, until finally, in 2008, he admitted they were true. He has shown no interest in meeting his son, Jonathan Berkery.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2008/12/14/tom-jones-admits-he-is-father-of-us-singer-91466-22470948|title=Tom Jones admits he is father of US singer|work=Wales Online|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|election of a Labour government in 1974]], Jones became a [[tax exile]] to avoid a 98 per cent income tax.<ref name=\"closeup\"/> In June 1976, he purchased the red-brick mansion at [[363 Copa De Oro Road]] in the [[East Gate Bel Air, Los Angeles|East Gate Old Bel Air in Los Angeles]] from [[Dean Martin]] for $500,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/welsh-homes/8000-semi-6m-bel-air-8631385|title=From the \u00a38,000 semi to $6m Bel Air mansion, inside the houses Sir Tom Jones has called home|work=Wales Online|date=12 February 2015|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> He sold it to [[Nicolas Cage]] in 1998 for a reported $6.469&nbsp;million. In 2009, after 35 years in the US, Jones said that he and his wife were planning to move back to the UK. \"I've had a great time living in Los Angeles\", Jones said, \"but after all these years, we think now is the time to move home\".<ref name=\"Tom Jones Bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/a163139/tom-jones-moving-back-to-britain.html|title=Tom Jones 'moving back to Britain'|work=Digital Spy|date=2 July 2009|accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015 his autobiography, ''Over the Top and Back: The Autobiography'', was published by [[Michael Joseph (publisher)|Michael Joseph]].<ref>{{cite book|date=8 October 2015| first= Tom |last= Jones|isbn=978-0-7181-8068-3|title=Over the Top and Back: The Autobiography| publisher= Michael Joseph}}</ref> Reviewing the book in the ''[[Daily Express]]'', Clair Woodward said, \"In the tradition of so many autobiographies these days, Tom Jones's doesn't tell you what you really want to hear. ... What you are left with is a riotously enjoyable story of Jones 'The Voice' which nicely doubles as the story of British pop and light entertainment from the Sixties onwards.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Woodward |first=Clair |url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/books/609200/Over-The-Top-And-Back-The-Autobiography-Sir-Tom-Jones-Leading-Dictator-book-review |title=Book reviews: Over The Top And Back: The Autobiography |work=Daily Express|date=2 October 2015|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nLinda, Lady Woodward, died on 10 April 2016 at [[Cedars-Sinai Medical Center|Cedars Sinai Hospital]] in Los Angeles, after a \"short but fierce\" battle with cancer, with Jones cancelling concerts at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-36015366|title=Sir Tom Jones's wife Lady Melinda Rose Woodward dies|publisher=BBC News|date=11 April 2016|accessdate=28 May 2016}}</ref> After her death, Jones sold their Los Angeles mansion and its contents, apart from treasured photos, and moved back to the UK. He resides in a flat in London, as she suggested.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/901147/tom-jones-wife-linda-lung-cancer-dying-wish-LA-home-london-the-voice-UK| title= Sir Tom Jones confesses he moved to London to fulfil his late wife's dying wish| first= Julia| last= Kuttner| date= January 7, 2018 |website= express.co.uk| publisher= | access-date= March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural influence==\n[[Space (English band)|Space]] and [[Cerys Matthews]] released \"[[The Ballad of Tom Jones]]\", a song about a fighting couple who are calmed down by listening to Jones's music on the radio. The song reached No. 4 in the UK in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spacetheband.com/discography/singles/the-ballad-of-tom-jones|title=The Ballad of Tom Jones the Single by Space \u2013 Discography|publisher=Space the Band|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nA new musical, ''Tom: A Story of Tom Jones'', based on the singer's life and recordings, produced by Theatr na n\u00d3g, opened at the [[Wales Millennium Centre]] in March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/tomthemusical/photos/a.595559490546690/672986666137305/?type=3&theater|title=Tom the Musical Facebook photo|work=Facebook|access-date=27 August 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=March 2020}}</ref> Reviewing the show for ''[[The Stage]]'', Mark Shenton wrote:\n\n<blockquote>...the show itself, written by Mike James and directed by Geinor Styles, is a more humdrum\u2014while hummable\u2014affair than its star and subject deserves. In the familiar jukebox musical style of shows like [[Jersey Boys]] and [[Beautiful: The Carole King Musical|Beautiful]], \"A Story of Tom Jones\" charts the behind-the-scenes rise to fame of a pop star, but without the craft or polish.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shenton|first=Mark|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/2016/tom-story-tom-jones-musical-review-wales-millennium-centre-cardiff-lacks-dramatic-meat|title=Tom: A Story of Tom Jones, the Musical review at Wales Millennium Centre, Cardiff \u2013 'lacks dramatic meat'|website=The Stage |date=10 March 2016|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nSimilar to [[Elvis Presley]] with his [[Elvis impersonator|impersonators]], Tom Jones has his share of [[Tom Jones impersonator|imitators]] around the world. These are performers who either sound like him or imitate his act.<ref>''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', 11 April 2018 \u2013 [https://www.latimes.com/sports/hockey/la-sp-kings-golden-knights-elliott-20180411-story.html Golden Knights give Vegas a real sense of community]</ref><ref>''Billboard'', 9 May 1998 \u2013 [https://books.google.com/books?id=UQ0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA60 Page 60 Newsmakers, '''Now The Real Thing.''']</ref><ref>''[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]'', Saturday, 7 July 2007 \u2013 [https://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2007/07/07/warren-makes-time-for-grandson/ Warren makes time for grandson by Stuart Michael]</ref>\n\nIn the 2006 film ''[[Flushed Away]]'', the main character Roddy is mistaken for Tom Jones by another character while Roddy performs \"[[She's a Lady]]\". Jones's song, \"[[What's New Pussycat? (song)|What's New Pussycat?]]\", is played during the ending credits.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nIn the video game ''[[Team Fortress 2]]'', one of the playable characters the Scout is a collector of Tom Jones' merchandise, and upon his death in the comics one of the other characters, the Spy falsely convinces him that Tom Jones is in fact his father. Tom Jones is also depicted using the phrase \"What's new pussycat?\" several times.<ref>''[[Team Fortress 2]]'', 10 January 2017 \u2013 [http://www.teamfortress.com/tf06_thenakedandthedead/ TF Comics 6: The Naked and the Dead]</ref>\n\n==Selected discography==\n{{Main|Tom Jones discography}}\n{{div col}}\n*''[[Along Came Jones (album)|Along Came Jones]]'' (1965)\n*''[[What's New Pussycat? (Tom Jones album)|What's New Pussycat?]]'' (1965)\n*''[[A-tom-ic Jones]]'' (1966)\n*''[[From the Heart (Tom Jones album)|From the Heart]]'' (1966)\n*''[[Green, Green Grass of Home (album)|Green, Green Grass of Home]]'' (1967)\n*''[[Delilah (Tom Jones album)|Delilah]]'' (1968)\n*''[[Help Yourself (Tom Jones album)|Help Yourself]]'' (1968)\n*''[[Reload (Tom Jones album)|Reload]]'' (1999)\n*''[[Mr. Jones (Tom Jones album)|Mr. Jones]]'' (2002)\n*''Tom Jones & Jools Holland'' {{small|(with [[Jools Holland]])}} (2004)\n*''24 Hours'' (2008)\n*''[[Praise & Blame]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Spirit in the Room]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Long Lost Suitcase]]'' (2015)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Compositions==\nJones wrote or co-wrote the following songs: \"And I Tell the Sea\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/chronicles-mw0000174224|title=Chronicles \u2013 Tom Jones|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref> \"Looking Out My Window\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/looking-out-my-window-mt0013407112|title=Looking Out My Window \u2013 Tom Jones|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref> \"Feel the Rain\"  from the 2002 ''[[Mr. Jones (Tom Jones album)|Mr. Jones]]'' album,<ref name=\"mrjones\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/mr-jones-mw0000457994|title=Mr. Jones \u2013 Tom Jones|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=4 August 2013}}</ref> \"Jezebel\",<ref name=\"mrjones\"/> \"The Letter\",<ref name=\"mrjones\"/> \"Younger Days\",<ref name=\"mrjones\"/> \"Tom Jones International\",<ref name=\"mrjones\"/> \"Holiday\",<ref name=\"mrjones\"/> \"The Road\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/3276580/Sir-Tom-Jones-writes-love-song-for-wife-Linda.html|title=Sir Tom Jones writes love song for wife Linda|work=The Telegraph|date=29 October 2008|accessdate=4 August 2013|last1=Irvine|first1=Chris}}</ref> \"24 Hours\",<ref name=\"24h\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/24-hours-mw0000802615|title=24 Hours \u2013 Tom Jones|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=4 August 2013}}</ref> \"Seasons\",<ref name=\"24h\"/> \"We Got Love\",<ref name=\"24h\"/> \"Seen That Face\",<ref name=\"24h\"/> \"Give a Little Love\",<ref name=\"24h\"/> \"If He Should Ever Leave You\",<ref name=\"24h\"/> \"Whatever it Takes\",<ref name=\"mrjones\"/> and \"Traveling Shoes\" from the 2012 album ''[[Spirit in the Room]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/spirit-in-the-room-mw0002348561|title=Spirit in the Room \u2013 Tom Jones|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=4 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!| Year\n!| Title\n!| Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[What's New Pussycat?]]''\n|  rowspan=\"3\" | Theme Singer\n| \n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[Promise Her Anything]]''\n| \n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]''\n|\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''The Special London Bridge Special''\n|   rowspan=\"2\" | \n|  a fantasy story about [[London Bridge]] being brought to America\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''On Happiness Island''\n| [[BBC]] special\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Pleasure Cove]]''\n| Raymond Gordon\n|  US TV Movie\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Fantasy Island]]''\n| Dick Turpin\n|  ([[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] series; season 7, episode 19)\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''The Ghosts of Oxford Street''\n|  Gordon Selfridge\n| Christmas TV Movie celebrating the 200th anniversary of London's Oxford Street\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[The Simpsons]]''\n|  rowspan=\"2\" | as Himself\n|  \"[[Marge Gets a Job]]\"\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Fresh Prince of Bel-Air]]''\n|  Season 3 Episode 18 : The {{sic|Alma Matter|hide=y|expected=Alma Mater}}\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''Silk n' Sabotage''\n|  Photographer\n|  \n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[The Jerky Boys: The Movie]]''\n|  rowspan=\"3\" | as Himself\n|  \n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Mars Attacks!]]''\n|  \n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Agnes Browne]]''\n|  \n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Emperor's New Groove]]''\n|   Theme Song Guy\n|  (animated film)\n|-\n| 2004\n|  ''[[Duck Dodgers (TV series)|Duck Dodgers]]''\n|   rowspan=\"2\" | as himself\n|  \"Talent Show A Go-Go\"<ref>[http://tomjonesonline.com/tom-jones-filmography.php]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090323050706/http://tomjonesonline.com/tom-jones-filmography.php |date=23 March 2009 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012\u201315, 2017\u2013\n| ''[[The Voice UK]]''\n|  Coach or \"judge\" and mentor for artists, Seasons 1 until 4 and 6 onwards\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Playhouse Presents]]''\n|   Ron\n|  Episode: \"King of the Teds\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Under Milk Wood]]''\n|   Captain Cat\n|  TV Film\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Superheroes Unite for BBC Children in Need]]''\n|   as Himself\n|  TV Film\n|}\n\n==Accolades==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=November 2017}}\n*1966: [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best New Artist]]\n*1966: Grammy Award ''nomination'' for Contemporary Rock & Roll Male Vocal Performance for \"What's New Pussycat?\"\n*1966: Grammy Award ''nomination'' for Contemporary Rock & Roll Single for \"It's Not Unusual\"\n*1970: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]] for ''This Is Tom Jones''\n*1970: [[Ivor Novello Award]] for International Artist of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theivors.com/archive/1970-1979/the-ivors-1970/|title=The Ivors 1970 \u2013 The Ivors|website=Theivors.com|accessdate=11 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307082550/http://theivors.com/archive/1970-1979/the-ivors-1970/|archive-date=7 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*1989: [[MTV Video Music Award \u2013 Breakthrough Video]] for \"Kiss\"\n*1989: Star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]\n*1999: appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE)<ref>{{cite news |title=New Years Honors List 1999 |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/55354/data.pdf |newspaper=The London Gazette}}</ref>\n*2000: [[2000 Brit Awards|Brit Award]] for Best British Male\n*2003: [[2003 Brit Awards|Brit Award]] for Outstanding Contribution to Music\n*2006: Knighthood for \"services to music\"\n*2017: [[Bambi Award]] in the category \"legend\"\n\n==See also==\n\n* {{books-inline|Tom Jones|Tom Jones}}\n* [[List of Welsh musicians]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bert Schwartz: ''Tom Jones'' ([[Grosset & Dunlap]], New York City, 1969) 76-103307\n* Peter Jones: ''Tom Jones: Biography of a Great Star'' ([[Avon Publishing]], 1970 (1st edition), 1971)\n* Colin MacFarlane: ''Tom Jones: The Boy from Nowhere'' ([[W. H. Allen]], London, 1988 St Martins Press, New York) {{ISBN|0-491-03118-1}}\n* Stafford Hildred & David Gritten: ''Tom Jones: A Biography'' (Isis Large Print Books, April 1991) {{ISBN|1-85089-486-8}}\n* Roger St. Pierre: ''Tom Jones: Quote Unquote'' (Parragon Book Service Ltd, Great Britain, 1996) {{ISBN|0-7525-1696-5}}\n* Stafford Hildred & David Gritten:  ''Tom Jones: A Biography'' (revised edition '98) ([[Sidgwick & Jackson]], 1998 an imprint of [[Macmillan Publishers]] Ltd) {{ISBN|0-283-06312-2}}\n* Chris Roberts:  ''Tom Jones'' (1st edition) ([[Virgin Books]], 1999 an imprint of Virgin Publishing Limited) {{ISBN|1-85227-846-3}}\n* Lucy Ellis, Bryony Sutherland: ''Tom Jones: Close Up'' ([[Omnibus Press]], 2000)  {{ISBN|0-7119-7549-3}} (HC) {{ISBN|0-7119-8645-2}} (Pb)\n* Robin Eggar: ''Tom Jones: The Biography'' (1st edition) (Headline Book Publishing, 2000) {{ISBN|0-7472-7578-5}}\n* ''Woodward v. Berkery'', 714 So.2d 1027 (Fla.App.4thDist. 1998)\n* Tom Jones: ''Over the Top and Back: The Autobiography'' ([[Michael Joseph (publisher)|Michael Joseph]], 8 October 2015) {{ISBN|0-7181-8068-2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.tomjones.com}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/57c6f649-6cde-48a7-8114-2a200247601a#p00b8ssm BBC Tom Jones Biography]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/music/sites/tom-jones/ BBC Wales Music]\n* [http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0311/07/lkl.00.html Transcript of interview with Larry King 7 November 2003]\n* {{IMDb name|429367|Tom Jones}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Shirley Bassey]]<br /><small>''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'', 1964</small>}} \n{{s-ttl|title=''[[James Bond]]'' title artist|years=<small>''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'', 1965</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nancy Sinatra]]<br /><small>''[[You Only Live Twice (fi